@node "MANUAL" "VLT Manual"

   The VLT manual is an official publication by the Stanford Linear
   Accelerator Center. You can obtain it, free of charge, by writing to
   the following address:

       Publications Department
       M.S. 68
       Stanford Linear Accelerator Center
       P.O. Box 4349
       Stanford, CA 94309

   or by sending e-mail to:

       techpub@slac.stanford.edu

   Ask for the following SLAC report:

       "A Valiant Little Terminal - A VLT User's Manual"
       SLAC Report 370
       by Amanda Weinstein

   The manual is very complete, it is 144 pages in single-spaced fairly small
   type. Amanda did one heck of a job on it, as I'm sure you'll find out when
   you get it. You do not have to live in the US to be eligible to receive the
   manual. The manual is *only* available in printed form.

   It was originally written for version 4.824, but it has since been revised
   three times and currently reflects the status of version 5.576 (the previous
   release of VLT). New features are described in this guide, but it is assumed
   you have the printed manual. It is currently not clear if the printed manual
   will be revised again. Even if so, it is going to take a while in any case.

   Please do not write the Publications Department about problems with the
   program, or for copies or updates of the software itself. They do not
   have access to such, nor can you depend on them passing your letters on to
   me. For problems, suggestions and other comments, please @{"write me" link AUTHOR} directly.

   Please do not write to me for the manual - I only have a few copies, and
   will have to forward your message to the publications department.
@endnode

@node "CHANGES_5576" "Changes since version 5.576"

   The changes in VLT since the last release, 5.576, can be categorized
   as follows:

   @{" General                  " link ch_general}
   @{" Requesters               " link ch_requesters}
   @{" Menus                    " link ch_menus}
   @{" Fonts                    " link ch_fonts}
   @{" Script Language          " link ch_script}
   @{" Miscellaneous            " link ch_misc}
   @{" Scripts and ARexx macros " link ch_macros}
   @{" Bug Fixes                " link ch_bugs}
@endnode

@node ch_general "General"

   One of the major changes in VLT is that it now uses a lot of system
   functions that are available since AmigaDOS 2.04. This also means that
   @{b}VLT will no longer run under AmigaDOS 1.3!@{ub} If you try to use VLT
   under 1.3 or older versions of AmigaDOS, then you will see a requester
   explaining that it is really time to upgrade.

   This version of VLT was compiled and linked using SAS/C version 6.51.
   It now uses the SC and SD link options, which makes the executable 
   considerably smaller. It also uses the very latest (v40.15) Amiga
   includes and amiga.lib.

   Where possible, VLT uses ASL requesters. All remaining requesters are
   generated using GadTools gadgets. VLT also uses GadTools menus wherever
   menus are used, and for those using AmigaDOS 3.0 or later, it uses 
   "new-look menus". The screen "function" gadgets are also GadTools.
   See also @{"Requesters" link ch_requesters} and @{"Menus" link ch_menus}.

   One of the new requesters VLT uses is the ASL Screen Mode requester.
   Since this requester is only available since AmigaDOS version 2.1, 
   you must have this version of the OS in order to be able to use it.
   You will be notified of this if you try to select the corresponding
   menu item under 2.04. If you still do use 2.04, then you can still use
   the ARexx program 2.04ScreenMode.vlt, see @{"Scripts and ARexx Macros" link ch_macros}.

   VLT no longer uses arp.library and screenshare.library. However, these
   are still used by rexxarplib.library, and if you use rexxarplib.library
   (which is used by a lot of the ARexx scripts included here), then you
   must leave these libraries installed in libs:. Note: The recently
   released rexxarplib.library version 3.3 no longer needs screenshare.library
   under 2.0x or later.
   See also @{"Scripts and ARexx macros" link ch_macros}.

   The review.library was merged into VLT - you can delete it from your
   system if you still have a copy.

   VLT has also become fully font sensitive, and you can now choose any
   fonts you like (with certain restrictions depending on what the font
   is used for - see @{"Fonts" link ch_fonts}.

   Traps are now synchronous with the updating of the screen display. If
   you use the ON, WAIT or TRAP commands, this may have certain
   @{"surprising consequences" link ch_traps}.

   VLT now has hypertext help, using this AmigaGuide database. This also means
   that the MenuHelp.vlt script is now obsolete and no longer supplied. You
   may delete it from your system.

   The SetMiscFlags.vlt script was replaced by a new Miscellaneous Options
   menu and requester.

   There were various additions and some changes to the @{"Script Language" link ch_script}.
   There were a number of @{"Miscellaneous" link ch_misc} changes, and various
   @{"Bug Fixes" link ch_bugs}.

   To all the @{"beta-testers" link betatesters}, I say thank you very much!
@endnode

@node neatstuff "NeatStuff.scp"

   The NeatStuff.scp script sets up the User menu and programs the mouse
   so that holding down a qualifier key while clicking the mouse causes
   interesting things to happen, and also a few other key strokes.

   If you are upgrading from a previous version of VLT, then you may
   want to run the NeatStuff.scp script. New users of VLT will find that
   VLT has all these settings by default (from Orig_VTPrefs.dat).

   In any case, if you decide you like these settings, then just save the
   configuration. Then you don't need to run NeatStuff.scp again.

   The default User menu programs are:

   VLT Phone Book                 Runs the VLT Phonebook ARexx program
   ScreenMode for 2.04 Users      Runs an ARexx ScreenMode requester
   Hayes Modem Hangup             Does the +++ delay ATH sequence
   Send Signature                 Example signature
   Send ASCII file                Example ASCII file transfer
   Toggle Screen Title Bar        What the menu item says
   About the VLT Manual           How to get the printed version
   Display Time - Date - Memory   Does what it says
   Print Screen                   Sends the screen text to the printer
   Menu Help                      Tells you how to get here

   Here's what the default programming is for the mouse. Clicking the left
   mouse button while holding down:

   no key               Undoes the selected area if any is visible.
   shift                Send mouse moves to the host position the cursor.
   ctrl                 Drag out an area. The area stays highlighted.
   alt                  Sends selected area clipboard and then to the host.
   shift ctrl           Selects a "word" on the screen.
   shift alt            Shows column and row of where the mouse was clicked.
   ctrl alt             BIX: resigns the conference/topic name you click on.
   shift ctrl alt       Sends selected area to the serial port plus spaces
                        so the text starts where you clicked.

   In addition the following keystrokes are also programmed:

   alt 0 (on keypad)    Saves selected area to clipboard and unselects.
   shift alt 0 ("")     Saves selected area to clipboard and unselects.
   alt . (on keypad)    Unselects the selected area
   shift alt . ("")     Unselects the selected area
   alt Enter (keyp.)    Sends the clipboard contents to the host.
   shift alt Enter ("") Sends the clipboard contents to the host, but
                        allows you to edit each line.

   alt cursor keys      Move the selected area around.

   shift alt cursor ks. Change the size of the selected area.
@endnode

