@node ch_traps "Trap Checking"

   Traps are now synchronous with the updating of the screen display. If
   you use the ON, WAIT or TRAP commands, this may have certain surprising
   consequences. Before, traps would be tested for first, and then the
   current text buffer would be displayed on the screen. With fast modems
   and large buffers of data, this has become more obvious. Now, the text
   is displayed on the screen simultaneous with checking for traps, and the
   trap is handled immediately upon putting the final trapping character on
   the screen.

   Also, trap checking is now performed for all text that is displayed on the
   screen, no matter how it got there. This means that specifically the output
   from Fifo pipes and the "emit" command is now checked - before it wasn't.

   Note that because of this, the following can cause an infinite recursion:

      on (connect) emit (Connecting to BIX...)

   To prevent VLT from running out of stack, VLT will now disallow high levels
   of (>20) recursion in the screen output routines.
@endnode

@node ch_requesters "Requesters"

   VLT now uses the ASL screen mode requester, and you can now also select
   modes added by such third-party graphics cards as the Picasso II board.
   All VLT code that still depended on the concepts of "interlace" or "no
   interlace" was fixed. VLT will now also allow a 16-color main screen, but
   use on non-AGA systems is discouraged.

   All ASL requesters remember their own previous positions and sizes. They
   are now saved in the config file.

   VLT now uses various GadTools based requesters. They are all font sensitive
   and resizable. Most of them remember their position and size, and these
   values are saved in the configuration files.

   One of these is the new @{"serial settings requester" link ITEM_serial}.
   Baud-rates up to 115.200 bps are now supported.

   The new Palette requester is very similar to the old one, except it can
   be resized. Its size and position are however not saved in the config file.

   The VLT message window has turned into a scrollable listview, which can
   keep track of some 100 or so messages that may have occurred before. A
   new menu item allows one to view this list, so one can scroll through
   the message history.

   The ARexx script SetMiscFlags.vlt was replaced by a built-in listview-style
   requester.

   Some simple "Okay/Cancel" requesters were replaced by "EasyRequest"s.

   The transfer status display was also rewritten, but is functionally similar
   to the one in previous versions of VLT. It is now resizable.

   VLT previously had a somewhat cumbersome method of changing menu
   abbreviations. A new requester, again listview-style, makes the procedure
   considerably easier. Moreover, the menu abbreviations for the Graphics 
   screen and those of the session history window can now be also be changed.
@endnode

@node ch_fonts "Fonts"

   VLT now allows you to choose three different fonts for text display. They
   are called Large, Normal and Small. When VLT needs to display text, it
   will select the largest font that fits, given the current settings of
   number of lines and columns to be displayed. If none of the fonts fit, 
   then it will use the largest font for which the condition holds that
   going to a smaller one wouldn't actually improve things. The VLT text
   can now be any size font that is mono-spaced.

   VLT is also otherwise completely font-sensitive: All requesters will use
   the current screen font, unless that font is proportional and the requester
   requires (usually for alignment purposes) a mono-spaced font. When VLT is
   on the Workbench, the screen font is that of the Workbench. When VLT is
   on its own custom screen, the font is the System Screen font, but you can
   select a different one. When you select a proportional font, you can also
   specify a mono-spaced font that will then be used wherever a proportional
   font is not usable.

   All fonts and their sizes are saved in the config file.

   The VT100 "graphics character set" fonts (vltgraph.font and
   vltgraph132.font) will now be scaled to the height and width of the text
   font currently in use. Since these fonts were designed to be 8 x 8 or
   8 x 11 pixels in size, this may lead to some ugly glyphs, but then, these
   fonts are really only used for block graphics, and there the glyphs will
   look allright.
@endnode

@node ch_menus "Menus"

   VLT now uses GadTools menus, and under AmigaDOS 3.0 and higher it uses
   new-look menus. In order to ensure that the menu background conforms to
   the style required by new-look menus (bright, with dark text), VLT now
   also sets the pens for these two colors automatically. However, if you
   insist, you can override this feature using a @{"miscflags option" link ch_misc}.

   Some menu items were removed because of various changes in the program.
   Since most of the serial device parameters are now set in a requester,
   all those menu items have disappeared. The "ANSI colors" subitem in the
   "Rendering mode" item was also removed - ANSI colors is now the default.
   People that still must use the older non-ANSI usage can defeat the 
   default using another @{"miscflags option" link ch_misc}.

   Menu text was in several places made more consistent and where possible
   more descriptive. All menu items that had On and Off subitems were
   replaced with check-marked menu items.

   The programming procedure for the menu abbreviations (keyboard shortcuts)
   was completely replaced by a new requester. Moreover, the keyboard 
   shortcuts for the Graphics windows and the Session History window can also
   be programmed. These are of course saved in the config file.

   Several menu options were added - see the sections describing the new
   menus.
@endnode

@node ch_script "Script Language"

   The following script commands were modified or added.

   @{" buffersize     " link sc_buff}
   @{" capture        " link sc_capt}
   @{" color          " link sc_colo}
   @{" customscreen   " link sc_cust}
   @{" extract        " link sc_extr}
   @{" file           " link sc_file}
   @{" font           " link sc_font}
   @{" message        " link sc_mess}
   @{" miscflags      " link sc_misc}
   @{" on             " link sc_wait}
   @{" transfer       " link sc_xfer}
   @{" trap           " link sc_wait}
   @{" wait           " link sc_wait}
   @{" xpr            " link sc_xfer}
@endnode

@node sc_buff "Buffersize"

   There is now a script option to set stdio and fastxpr buffer sizes:

      buffersize stdio <n>       set stdio buffer size
      buffersize xprfast <n>     set fast xpr routine buffer size (see
                                 @{"miscflags" link sc_misc})
      buffersize serial <n>      set serial buffer size
      buffersize <n>             set serial buffer size (compatibility)
@endnode

@node sc_capt "Capture"

   The capture command now allows the "append" keyword to be used:

      capture append <filename>

   Another new keyword is "verbose". When it is used, any errors that may
   occur will be displayed in the message window.
@endnode

@node sc_colo "Color"

   The color command has some new pens that can be assigned with the color
   spec. They are bardetailpen, barblockpen and bartrimpen.
@endnode

@node sc_cust "Customscreen"

   The customscreen command has been enhanced to allow specifying the screen
   that needs to be opened in much greater detail. The new syntax is:

      customscreen [mode <modeid>] [width <width>] [height <height>]
                   [overscan <overscan>] [autoscroll <autoscroll>]
                   [depth <depth>]

   Most of these options will force VLT to open a custom screen. The
   overscan clip rect is specified as a number between 1 and 4. When 
   <autoscroll> is non-zero, autoscroll will be enabled, otherwise disabled.

   For compatibility, VLT will also continue to recognize the old syntax
   which only provided switching capability between Workbench use and 
   custom screen mode:

      customscreen {on | off | yes | no | toggle}
@endnode

@node sc_extr "Extract"

   The Extract command now can extract a number of new items.

   - screenparams    Screen parameters in the sequence:
                     modeid width height overscan autoscroll depth

   - progdir         The current default directory.

   - serialstatus    The "flags" field of the IORequest after a SDCMD_QUERY.
                     Among other things, bit 5 should track carrier status
                     if the modem asserts the CD line properly.

   The extract command now also has an optional second argument.

      extract <item> <portname>

   When given, the value of the item(s) is sent to the ARexx message port
   with name <portname> as arg0 of the ARexx message in the form:

   <item> = <value>
@endnode

@node sc_file "File"

   The file send and file receive commands now will return error codes
   in case of failed up/downloads. Note that it is impossible to determine
   if an automatically started download has failed.
@endnode

@node sc_font "Font"

   The font command has changed. The syntax now is:

   font [{large | normal | small | screen | monospaced}] [size <n>] <name>

   The defaults are "normal" and size 8.
   Note that setting the screen font from a script does *not* close the screen
   and reopen it automatically.
@endnode

@node sc_mess "Message"

   A message command with an empty string pops up the message requester.
   As before, a message command with no string at all will remove the 
   requester.
@endnode

@node sc_misc "Miscflags"

   The miscflags script command now has the following added options:

   - noautopens         do not automatically assign shadow/shine and
                        menu pens during OpenScreen.

   - fastxprio          use double-buffered XPR IO routines. This 
                        option may not always work correctly, and should
                        only be used after establishing that it doesn't
                        cause problems.

   - abuseansicolors    use ANSI color sequences <esc>[40m and <esc>[41m
                        in SLAC defined ways.

   - margins            display left and right margins

   - nodisplayescape    Treat <esc> as a non-display character.
   - echoconsole        Echo lines you type in the console window to the
                        screen as well, when in local echo mode.
@endnode

@node sc_wait "Wait, On, Trap"

   Trap checking is now synchronous with text display. This is true for all
   trap, on and wait generated traps.

   Traps generated using the "trap" command now allow wildcards, when the 
   "wild" option is used. The only wildcard allowed is the "?" character,
   which matches exactly one character.
@endnode

@node sc_xfer "Transfer, XPR"

   Changed XPR selection procedure in the script language. Everything should
   still work, compatibility-wise, but the procedure has become easier.
   Externally, it all should still work the same, more or less, but internally
   it was changed significantly. The way it used to work was:

      transfer protocol {kermit | xmodem | external}

   So, to select kermit or xmodem was easy, but to select an external protocol
   you had to do:

      transfer protocol external
      xpr select <xprname>.library

   This did allow the situation where the user's external protocol name was,
   say xprfoo.library, but his current settings were for XMODEM. Doing a
   "transfer protocol external" would then select xprfoo.library without the
   need for the xpr select command. ***This is no longer the case***.
   The "transfer protocol external" command now no longer does anything. The
   command syntax now is:

      transfer protocol {kermit | xmodem | ascii | quickb | zmodem | ymodem}

   When one wants to select a protocol other than the ones formed by prepending
   "xpr" to this and appending ".library", then the only command that needs to
   be given is:

      xpr select <xprname>.library

   The "transfer protocol external" part is now implicit. For compatibility,
   the command can still be given but it will not do anything.
@endnode


@node ch_bugs "Bug Fixes"

   The following bugs were fixed:

   - The cursor used to be one pixel too wide.

   - The command line -s option didn't work if the serial device name was
     saved in the config file.

   - Hitting arrow keys while browsing through the Session History could
     cause arrow key sequences to be sent to the host.

   - Using the "Save" menu item in the session history window would 
     indeed save, despite the fact that nothing was highlighted in the
     review buffer, causing it to erase the data in the current file.

   - Similarly, saving to the clipboard from the session history window
     while nothing was highlighted, and then inserting the clipboard context
     for example into an editor could cause problems.

   - A bug was fixed in the prescrolling code.

   - A long-standing bug in the prototype for the CheckIO() function was
     fixed by Commodore. VLT now uses include files that have this fixed.

   - When selecting file transfer protocols from a script, the menu used to
     specify that an "Other" protocol was in effect.

   - When selecting an XPR whose library was not available, VLT would appear
     to correctly revert to the previous protocol, but in fact it would not.

   - When trap checking was made synchronous with text display, the
     likelihood of infinite recursion became much greater. A fix was installed
     to prevent this.

   - The Extract command did not properly extract the current transfer
     protocol in some cases.

   - There was a memory leak in the "wedge" command.

   - Various bugs in the owndevunit.library support were fixed.

   - A wrapping problem was fixed where characters could wind up sticking out
     beyond the last column on the right.

   - Some problems were solved when selecting XPR's whose files can't be found.

   - In Tek mode, turning the graphics cursor on by hand from the menu, would
     cause Bypass mode to turn on. It was decided that that is usually not
     wanted.

   - Fixed up some problems when trying to position requesters on autoscrolling
     screens.

   - The way the serial device is opened has changed again. It now should no
     longer (a) open the device twice in rapid sequence if CTS/RTS was
     selected, (b) allow device names with mixed case (when typed in properly)
     and (c) keep the OwnDevUnit stuff in sync and (d) tries to open the device
     without path name to fix up broken OpenDevice setfunctioners.

   - All requesters now use "Okay" consistently
@endnode

@node ch_misc "Miscellaneous"

   Here are some miscellaneous changes.

   - While VLT no longer uses arp.library, it still uses @{"ARP-style escape" link cmd_ARP}
     sequences. The default "escape" character is still the * (asterisk).
     Arp.library used to check an env variable to allow users to change
     this to a different character. VLT now allows a new Command Line
     option, +e, to change the default. It also checks the environment
     variable ESCAPE. It only does this when VLT is started up. The command
     line option overrides the environment variable.

   - When VLT cannot find VTPrefs.dat, or the VTPrefs file specified using
     the +p option, then VLT will fall back to the file Orig_VTPrefs.dat
     which is now supplied in the s directory. If that file is also not
     present, then it will fail as before. Similarly for TekPrefs.dat.

   - There is a new Miscflags option, which allows one to set the <DEL>
     character to be non-display. VT100's do not display <DEL> characters,
     so for proper VT100 emulation one should turn this option on ("yes"),
     but for compatibility with previous versions, it is by default turned
     off.

   - If the direction of a file transfer is known, it is now displayed in
     the status requester title bar. However, when a download is started
     automatically, it is in principle difficult to determine in which
     direction the transfer will take place, and it will not be shown.

   - For those that want to do their own color selections and do not want to
     rely on VLT's choices for bardetail and -block pens, a new miscflag
     was added to disable this feature.

   - A new miscflags option was added which uses asynchronous I/O using
     Martin Taillefer's AsyncIO routines during XPR protocol transfers.
     However, the functionality of these routines is not completely identical
     to that of the standard IO routines, and this option may cause problems.
     If this is the case, do not use the option. If you find that the option
     works, use it: it speeds up transfers noticeably, in certain cases. One
     can set the buffer size used by the async routines using a new script
     option.

   - A new miscflags option exists that adds "margin lines" to your window.
     If you have a situation where the screen and font sizes are such that
     you have a lot of space on the left and right side of the screen, such
     margin lines may help tell you where the first and last column are.

   - Escape sequences that are sent out by VLT keystrokes (such as arrow keys
     and keypad keys) are now sent in one IO request. They used to be sent
     in stages (first the escape, then an intermediate character and then 
     the last character). This change is especially useful when working with
     connections over a network.

   - The RADBOOGIE flag used to be set only when no flow control was selected.
     It is now also used when CTS/RTS handshaking is selected, and all other
     conditions are met.

   - Trace messages (see the @{"Trace" link cmd_trace} script command) are now sent to the message
     window, if the console is not open.

   - For proper VT100 emulation, the top four keys of the keypad should send
     VT100 "F1" through "F4" sequences in both numeric and application modes.
     The previous versions of VLT did not do this - they sent the characters
     shown on the keycaps in numeric mode. There is now a miscflags option
     to make it behave like a VT100 in all cases.

   - The VLTConsoleMenus file in /s was fixed up to conform to the new menu
     items and texts.

   - The secondary size of review window is now stored in the configuration
     file when the configuration is saved.

   - The Fifo pipe code now performs carriage control translation and 8th-bit
     stripping, much like in the case of capture. It keys on whether "raw
     capture" is set and/or on whether 8th-bit stripping is enabled.

   - There is a new Miscflags option, which causes lines typed in the console
     window to be echoed to the screen in local echo mode. By default turned
     off.
@endnode

@node ch_macros "Scripts and ARexx Macros"

   The following scripts and macros were modified, added or removed.

   - The @{"NeatStuff.scp" link neatstuff} script was changed, tracking various new features
     of VLT. Some obsolete things were removed or replaced by more useful
     items. The "Orig_VTPrefs.dat" file uses the new NeatStuff, so only
     those that are upgrading from older versions of VLT may want to rerun
     this script.

   - FifoBBS.rexx now has several modem commands and other modifications
     to make it easier to set up a BBS. Previous versions got easily
     confused by the modem echoing strings back to VLT (and thus FifoBBS)
     causing FifoBBS to think someone was already trying to log on.
     The new version fixes the problem at the cost of some modem commands
     that are now in the FifoBBS.rexx code (see there). Also, an ARexx
     program called "RunBBS.rexx" is now included, which gives an example
     of how to start a BBS session. It uses the also included VTPrefsBBS.dat
     file. a prefs file that has Fifo pipes turned on. It starts up a session
     of VLT in the background (i.e. no screen or window open).  It runs the
     Carrier.vlt init script - this checks for carrier status and sends
     NO CARRIER to the BBS in order to get it to log the user out.
     Unfortunately, my modem doesn't seem to assert the CD signal when
     answering the phone, so this may not work. FifoBBS now also tries
     to set the terminal to "lfmode", which is a VT100 mode which
     automatically inserts CR characters for all linefeeds. If the person
     connecting to the BBS has a VT100-emulating terminal, that will cause
     it to work - previous versions required the capability to turn
     linefeeds into CR/LF pairs on the connecting-terminal side.


   - All ARexx scripts used to add rexxmathlib.library to the library list.
     As it happens, none of the scripts actually use rexxmathlib, so this
     was superfluous. Moreover, people who didn't have rexxmathlib would run
     into trouble because of this.

   - A remark on Rexxarplib.library: Some people request in their "addlib"
     or "rxlib" attempts a specific version of rexxarplib. Unfortunately, 
     rexxarplib does not properly initialize the version and revision fields
     in all the right places, so requesting version 3.0 does not work.
     Note: the recently released version 3.3 of rexxarplib fixes this.

   - The MenuHelp.vlt script is no longer included. It is now superseded by
     this AmigaGuide on-line help file. If you still have this macro, you
     may want to delete it.

   - The SetMiscFlags.vlt script is no longer included. It is now superseded
     by a new requester, accessed through a menu item in the Operation menu.
     If you still have this file, you may want to delete it.

   - A new ARexx macro called 2.04ScreenMode.vlt is now included: If you are
     running AmigaDOS 2.04, the ScreenMode requester is not part of
     asl.library. You can still set a new screen mode using this ARexx script.
@endnode

@node "PINGSERVER" "PingServer"
    NAME

	PingServer
	==========

    SYNOPSIS

	PingServer

    FUNCTION

	This program sets up a REXX server for a pleasant sounding 'Ping'
	noise. The duration, frequency and volume can be adjusted.

    ARGUMENTS

	None

    ADDITIONAL	CONSIDERATIONS

	This program opens a REXX port that one may send messages to.
	There are currently three different commands: BEEP, SET and QUIT.
	The SET command allows setting the defaults of duration, frequency,
	and volume in arguments 1, 2, and 3 of the REXX message, respectively
	(the command itself being in argument 0). The volume function is
	duplicated in the BEEP function as argument 1.
	This program detaches from the CLI.

	For an example of setting parameters, see also SetPing.rexx.

	This program used to be called Ping in previous releases. However,
	this name is commonly used in networking software, so it was renamed
        to PingServer.

    BUGS

	None known.

    AUTHOR/DATE

	W.G.J. Langeveld, 3 December 1988
        (renamed to PingServer on 24 March 1992).

@endnode

