@node ITEM_capture "Capture Session"

   Select a file to which all incoming text will be captured.
   When capture is on, toggles capture off and on.
@endnode
   
@node ITEM_endcapture "End Capture"

   Close the currently open capture file.
@endnode
   
@node ITEM_fifo "Fifo Pipes"

   Turn Fifo pipes on/off. See manual.
@endnode
   
@node ITEM_console "Open Console"

   Open the VLT Console (chat window). In program mode, allows
   changing the console string.
@endnode
   
@node ITEM_history "Show Session History"

   Open the history window. If already open, activate it. It has
   menus of its own.
@endnode
   
@node ITEM_messages "Show Recent messages"

   Show a list of recent messages.
@endnode
   
@node ITEM_default "Set Default Directory"

   A directory requester will come up to let you select the
   default directory.
@endnode
   
@node ITEM_program "Program Mode"

   Turn on/off Program Mode for all function keys and several
   programmable menus. Then select function key or menu you wish
   to program.
@endnode
   
@node ITEM_config "Save Configuration"

   Save the current settings to the configuration file. This is
   usually s/VTPrefs.dat.
@endnode
   
@node ITEM_configas "Save Configuration As"

   Save the current settings to a different configuration file.
@endnode
   
@node ITEM_about "About"

   Shows VLT version number and copyright notice.
@endnode
   
@node ITEM_help "Help"

   Shows this AmigaGuide help document.
@endnode
   
@node ITEM_exit "Exit"

   Exit VLT.
@endnode
   
@node ITEM_device "Set Device"

   Select a serial device. The default and normal Amiga serial
   device is devs:serial.device.
@endnode
   
@node ITEM_unit "Set Unit"

   Select a serial device unit. The default and normal Amiga
   serial unit is 0.
@endnode
   
@node ITEM_closedev "Close Device"

   Close the serial device.
@endnode
   
@node ITEM_serial "Serial Parameters"

   Opens a requester which allows one to set the following things:

   - Modem speed in bits per second (sometimes called baud).

   - Parity: No, Even, Odd, Mark or Space parity.

   - 7 or 8 bit data.

   - 1 or 2 stop bits.

   - Flow control. No flow control may cause data loss for large
     quantities of incoming or outgoing data. Xon/Xoff handshake
     works well for low modem speed (up to 2400 bps). Hardware
     flow control Works best for high speed modems. Xon/Xoff plus
     hardware flow control is almost never used.

   - The length of the break signal.
   
   - The size of the serial buffer. Default 2048, maximum 8192 bytes.

   - When Midi is selected as the modem speed, you can also set
     a baud rate different from the nominal value of 31250 bps.
   
   A set of checkmarks can be set to tell VLT to report an error when

   - the serial device is busy.
   - there is a baud rate mismatch.
   - there is a line error.
   - there is a parity error.
   - there is a buffer overflow.
   - there is no DSR signal. See modem manual.
   - a break signal is received.
@endnode
   
@node ITEM_echo "Echo"

   Turn local character echo of what you type on or off.
@endnode
   
@node ITEM_bit "Strip 8th Bit"

   When on, the 8th bit of each incoming character is set to
   zero.
@endnode
   
@node ITEM_reset "Reset"

   Reset the serial device. May lose the connection.
@endnode
   
@node ITEM_break "Send Break"

   Send a break signal to the remote host.
@endnode
   
@node ITEM_hangup "Hang Up"

   Hang up the phone by dropping DTR for one second. Does not
   work with all modems.
@endnode
   
@node ITEM_pcopy "Copy to ClipBoard"

   Copy the @{"highlighted" link ITEM_MOUSE} text to the clipboard.
@endnode
   
@node ITEM_pclip "Paste from ClipBoard"

   Send the contents of the clipboard to the host.
@endnode
   
@node ITEM_epclip "Edit/Paste Clipboard"

   Send the contents of the clipboard to the host, but display
   each line and allow it to be edited before sending.
@endnode
   
@node ITEM_pfile "Paste from File"

   Send the contents of a file to the host. Displays a file requester.
@endnode
   
@node ITEM_epfile "Edit/Paste File"

   Send the contents of a file to the host, but allow each line
   to be edited first.
@endnode
   
@node ITEM_pcancel "Cancel Paste"

   Cancel the paste operation currently in progress.
@endnode
   
@node ITEM_cdelay "Set Character Delay"

   Change the character delay. Default is 40 msec between
   characters.
@endnode
   
@node ITEM_ldelay "Set Line Delay"

   Change the line delay. Default is 1 second (1000 msec) between
   lines.
@endnode
   
@node ITEM_lprefix "Set Line Prefix"

   Select a prefix. This prefix is inserted before each line
   pasted.
@endnode
   
@node ITEM_send "Send File"

   Send a file to the host using the currently selected transfer
   protocol.
@endnode
   
@node ITEM_receive "Receive File"

   Receive a file from the host using the currently selected
   transfer protocol.
@endnode

@node ITEM_sub "Item has subitems"

   This item has subitems, and has no function when selected
   by itself.
@endnode
   
@node ITEM_proto "Protocol"

   Select one of the listed file transfer protocols.
@endnode
   
@node ITEM_prother "Protocol Other"

   Select a file transfer protocol that is not listed.
@endnode
   
@node ITEM_ksend "Send/Receive"

   Set Kermit mode to send and receive files one by one.
@endnode
   
@node ITEM_khost "Host is Server"

   Set Kermit mode for the host to be a server. "Receive File"
   now means "Get File".
@endnode
   
@node ITEM_kdown "Downcase File Names"

   Upon receiving files with Kermit, change the file names to
   lower case.
@endnode
   
@node ITEM_kbye "Kermit Bye"

   Send a Kermit Bye command.
@endnode
   
@node ITEM_kfin "Kermit Finish"

   Send a Kermit Finish command.
@endnode
   
@node ITEM_kpack "Set Packet Size"

   Change the Kermit packet size.
@endnode
   
@node ITEM_x "XMODEM Options"

   Set XMODEM options; use checksum or CRC (better), use 128 byte
   or 1K blocks (faster).
@endnode
   
@node ITEM_extopt "External Options"

   Change the settings of other protocols. These are not saved in
   the configuration. See protocol docs for info.
@endnode
   
@node ITEM_mode "File Transfer Mode"

   Switch file transfer mode between binary and text.
@endnode
   
@node ITEM_arexx "Execute ARexx Macro"

   Select an ARexx macro (.vlt script) to be executed.
@endnode
   
@node ITEM_native "Execute VLT Script"

   Select a native VLT script (.scp script) to be executed.
@endnode
   
@node ITEM_abort "Abort All Scripts"

   Abort all scripts. Tries to abort ARexx macros too, but can't
   always succeed.
@endnode
   
@node ITEM_remove "Remove All Traps"

   Remove all traps (these are "on", "wait" and "trap" script
   commands).
@endnode
   
@node ITEM_clear "Clear Screen"

   Erase the screen.
@endnode
   
@node ITEM_refresh "Refresh Screen"

   Refresh the screen contents.
@endnode
   
@node ITEM_toback "Move Screen to Back"

   Put the VLT screen(s) in back of all other screens.
@endnode
   
@node ITEM_custom "Custom Screen"

   Put VLT on its own custom screen. It is a public screen with
   default name VLT.
@endnode
   
@node ITEM_workbench "Workbench"

   Put VLT on the Workbench in a sizable/draggable window.
@endnode
   
@node ITEM_scrmode "Screen Mode"

   Set the VLT screen mode, screen size and number of colors.
@endnode
   
@node ITEM_palette "Palette"

   When VLT is on a custom screen, change the colors it uses.
@endnode

@node ITEM_scrfont "Set Screen Font"

   Set the screen font VLT uses when on a custom screen.
@endnode

@node ITEM_monofont "Set Mono-spaced Font"

   If the screen font is proportional, VLT will use the system default
   font when it can't use a proportional one (which is in many of the
   requesters). With this menu item you can choose a different font for
   that purpose.
@endnode

@node ITEM_largefont "Large Font"

   This is the largest text font VLT will use if it fits on the screen,
   given the specified number of lines and columns.
@endnode

@node ITEM_normfont "Normal Font"

   This is the second largest text font VLT will use if the largest does
   not fit on the screen but this one does, given the specified number
   of lines and columns.
@endnode

@node ITEM_smallfont "Small Font"

   This is the smallest text font VLT will use if the larger two  don't
   fit on the screen but this one does, given the specified number of
   lines and columns.
@endnode

@node ITEM_keymap "Set Special Key Map"

   Change the special keymap VLT uses. See manual.
@endnode
   
@node ITEM_lines "Set Number of Lines"

   Change the number of lines VLT should display. VLT will try to use 
   the biggest specified font that fits.
@endnode
   
@node ITEM_columns "Set Number of Columns"

   Change the number of columns VLT should display. VLT will try to
   use the biggest specified font that fits.
@endnode

@node ITEM_canscroll "Cancel Scroll Region"

   Many mainframe editors set scrolling regions, but few clear it
   later. If you find that after editing a file on the mainframe (or
   running another utility that sets a scroll region) you can only
   display a limited number of lines at the top of the screen, then
   you can select this item to fix it up.
@endnode

@node ITEM_scrollspeed "Set Scrolling Speed"

   Change the scrolling speed. Positive numbers indicate "jump
   scroll", negative numbers "smooth scroll".
@endnode
   
@node ITEM_curheight "Set Cursor Height"

   Change the cursor height (in pixels). Height > 8 means use
   font size.
@endnode
   
@node ITEM_quick "Quick"

   Use "quick" rendering mode. Only one bitplane is used in this
   mode. Scrolls fast, but no colors.
@endnode
   
@node ITEM_normrend "Normal"

   Use "normal" rendering mode. Somewhat slower, but uses a
   different color for "bold" style.
@endnode
   
@node ITEM_color "Color"

   Use all 8 colors. Boldface/blink/underline etc. are displayed
   with colors instead. In this mode, ANSI color sequences are also
   recognized.
@endnode
   
@node ITEM_scrclose "Close Screen"

   Close the screen. To reopen, run VLT again, or send the ARexx
   message "window open".
@endnode
   
@node ITEM_wrap "Wrap"

   When selected, character wrap is on. When the cursor reaches the
   last column, an automatic cr/lf is inserted.
@endnode
   
@node ITEM_repeat "Key Repeat"

   When selected, key-repeat is on. This should be the default, but
   can be changed from the host.
@endnode
   
@node ITEM_numkey "Numeric Keypad"

   When selected, the keypad sends numeric data (i.e. 1, 2, 3 etc.).
   May be changed from the host.
@endnode
   
@node ITEM_appcur "Application Cursor"

   When selected, the cursor keys send "application-mode" sequences.
@endnode
   
@node ITEM_bsdel "Swap BS <-> Delete"

   When selected, the functions of backspace and delete keys are
   reversed.
@endnode
   
@node ITEM_destbs "Destructive BS"

   When selected, all incoming backspace characters will erase the
   character under the cursor.
@endnode
   
@node ITEM_helplf "Help Key = LF"

   When selected, the help key will send a linefeed. Otherwise it
   send the same as the "+" on the keypad (this is an old Amiga 1000
   issue - A1000's don't have a full keypad).
@endnode
   
@node ITEM_shifttab "Shift-Tab = ESC TAB"

   When selected, shift + tab will send an escape followed by a
   tab. Otherwise, only a tab is sent. This is often useful on IBM
   mainframes.
@endnode
   
@node ITEM_function "Function Key Gadgets"

   When selected, function key gadgets are displayed at the bottom
   of the screen. These can be programmed in program mode.
@endnode
   
@node ITEM_echocrlf "CR Key: Echo CR/LF"

   When selected, the return key echos a return plus a linefeed
   rather than just a return.
@endnode
   
@node ITEM_sendcrlf "CR Key: Send CR/LF"

   When selected, the return key sends a return plus a linefeed
   rather than just a return.
@endnode
   
@node ITEM_dispcrcrlf "Display CR as CR/LF"

   When selected, incoming returns are displayed as returns plus
   linefeeds.
@endnode
   
@node ITEM_displfcrlf "Display LF as CR/LF"

   When selected, incoming linefeeds are displayed as returns plus
   linefeeds.
@endnode
   
@node ITEM_autoback "Auto-Screen to Back"

   When selected, the screen will automatically flip to the back
   during a transfer, with the status window on the Workbench.
@endnode
   
@node ITEM_mouse "Mouse Support"

   Displays a requester allowing reprogramming of all the mouse
   functions. The current default settings are described in the
   script called @{"NeatStuff.scp" link neatstuff}.
@endnode
   
@node ITEM_beepvol "Set Beep Volume"

   Allows setting the beep volume. Beep volume 0 means a screen
   flash. In program mode, allows changing the beep program.
@endnode

@node ITEM_menushort "Menu Shortcuts"

   Displays a requester allowing reprogramming of all the menu 
   shortcuts.
@endnode

@node ITEM_miscopt "Miscellaneous Options"

   Displays a requester which allows one to set miscellaneous 
   options and preferences.
@endnode

@node ITEM_lock "Lock Graphics"

   Prevent the screen from changing to graphics mode when certain
   control sequences are received.
@endnode
   
@node ITEM_tograph "To Graphics"

   Display the Tektronix graphics screen. Only for the full VLT
   graphics version, not for VLTjr.
@endnode

@node ITEM_hclear "Clear"

   Clear the history buffer, and erase the session history window.
@endnode

@node ITEM_hsave "Save"

   Save the selected lines in the session history window to the
   current file. This overwrites the contents of that file.
@endnode

@node ITEM_hsaveas "Save As"

   Save the selected lines in the session history window to a
   new file. Brings up a file requester. If the selected file
   already exists, a requester pops up to ask whether the file
   should be overwritten, appended to, or whether the operation
   should be canceled.
@endnode

@node ITEM_hsaveclip "Save to ClipBoard"

   Save the selected lines to the clipboard.
@endnode

@node ITEM_happend "Append"

   Append the selected lines to the current file.
@endnode

@node ITEM_happendto "Append To"

   Append the selected lines to a file. A file requester will be
   displayed.
@endnode

@node ITEM_insert "Insert New Page"

   Inserts a virtual page mark into the history buffer. This allows
   one to save a page of text as it currently is, and won't allow
   "page-mode" hosts or applications to overwrite this information.
@endnode

@node ITEM_buffersize "Set Buffer Size"

   Set the history buffer size. For speed reasons, the history
   buffer is somewhat wasteful of memory. To compute the number
   of lines that will be kept for a certain buffer size, divide
   it by the currently selected number of columns. For example,
   if your buffer size is 10,000, and your number of columns is
   80, then the number of lines in the history buffer is
   10,000/80 = 125.
@endnode

@node ITEM_hquit "Quit"

   Close the history window.
@endnode

@node ITEM_select "Select All"

   Select all available lines in the history buffer.
@endnode

@node ITEM_deselect "Deselect All"

   Deselect all available lines in the history buffer.
@endnode

@node ITEM_invsel "Invert Selection"

   Select all unselected lines in the history buffer and deselect
   all selected ones.
@endnode

@node ITEM_lineup "Line Up"

   Move up one line in the history window.
@endnode

@node ITEM_pageup "Page Up"

   Move up one page in the history window.
@endnode

@node ITEM_top "Top of Buffer"

   Move to the top line in the history window.
@endnode

@node ITEM_linedown "Line Down"

   Move down one line in the history window.
@endnode

@node ITEM_pagedown "Page Down"

   Move down one page in the history window.
@endnode

@node ITEM_end "End of Buffer"

   Move to the bottom line in the history window.
@endnode

@node ITEM_colleft "Column Left"

   Move left one column in the history window.
@endnode

@node ITEM_pageleft "Page Left"

   Move left one page in the history window.
@endnode

@node ITEM_leftmarg "Left Margin"

   Move to the left margin in the history window.
@endnode

@node ITEM_colright "Column Right"

   Move right one column in the history window.
@endnode

@node ITEM_pageright "Page Right"

   Move right one page in the history window.
@endnode

@node ITEM_rightmarg "Right Margin"

   Move to the right margin in the history window.
@endnode

@node ITEM_sfor "Search Forward"

   Search from the beginning of the history buffer to end for a
   word or phrase. A requester will ask for the text to search for.
@endnode

@node ITEM_srev "Search Reverse"

   Search from the end of the history buffer to beginning for a
   word or phrase. A requester will ask for the text to search for.
@endnode

@node ITEM_rsfor "Repeat Forward"

   Repeat the current search in the forward direction.
@endnode

@node ITEM_rsrev "Repeat Reverse"

   Repeat the current search in the reverse direction.
@endnode

@node ITEM_gsave "Save (VLT Format)"

   Save a picture in VLT binary format to the "current" file.
   This overwrites the information in that file.
@endnode

@node ITEM_gsaveas "Save As (VLT Format)"

   Save a picture in VLT binary format to a new file. A requester
   will ask for the filename.
@endnode

@node ITEM_gload "Load (VLT Format)"

   Load a picture that is in VLT binary format.
@endnode

@node ITEM_forget "Forget Loaded Picture"

   Forgets the loaded picture and redisplays the picture that was
   there previously (i.e. the picture that came in from the host
   most recently).
@endnode

@node ITEM_gsaveiff "Save As (IFF-Bitmap)"

   Saves a file as an IFF bitmap, so it can be imported into programs
   such as Deluxe Paint, or displayed on the screen using an IFF display
   program.
@endnode

@node ITEM_bitmax "Maximum Size"

   Prints the screen bitmap to the printer. Uses the maximum available
   size.
@endnode

@node ITEM_bit13 "1/3 Page"

   Prints the screen bitmap to the printer at 1/3 of a standard page size.
@endnode

@node ITEM_bit23 "2/3 Page"

   Prints the screen bitmap to the printer at 2/3 of a standard page size.
@endnode

@node ITEM_bitfull "Full Page"

   Prints the screen bitmap to the printer at standard page size.
@endnode

@node ITEM_gsavepost "Save As (PostScript®)"

   Save graphics as a PostScript file. A file requester will ask for the
   file name.
@endnode

@node ITEM_gsavescript "Save As (Script File)"

   Save graphics as a VLT script file. A file requester will ask for the
   file name. This script file can then be used to redisplay the graphics
   later. However, it is faster and consumes less space to save the graphics
   in VLT binary format. However, this form is suitable for editing since it
   is in plain text form.
@endnode

@node ITEM_zoom "Set Zoom Mode"

   Set Zoom mode. Now click somewhere in the graphics window and drag out a
   rectangle. The area spanned (and corrected for aspect ratio) will be
   redisplayed magnified to cover the screen.
@endnode

@node ITEM_pan "Set Pan Mode"

   Set Pan mode. Now click somewhere in the graphics window and drag the 
   rectangle representing the screen elsewhere. The area covered by the
   rectangle will be redisplayed.
@endnode

@node ITEM_fullview "Show Full View"

   Redisplay the picture unmagnified.
@endnode

@node ITEM_gcurson "Switch Graphics Cursor On"

   Display the graphics cursor (cross hair).
@endnode

@node ITEM_gcursoff "Switch Graphics Cursor Off"

   Remove the graphics cursor (cross hair).
@endnode

@node ITEM_chair "Display Cross Hair Only"

   When the graphics cursor is on, X or Y coordinates are not
   displayed numerically.
@endnode

@node ITEM_chairxy "Display Cross Hair + XY"

   When the graphics cursor is on, the X and Y coordinates are also
   displayed numerically in the corner of the window.
@endnode

@node ITEM_gcustom "Open on Custom Screen"

   Open the graphics window on its own custom screen.
@endnode

@node ITEM_gmain "Use Main VLT Window"

   The graphics will be displayed in the same window as the text.
@endnode

@node ITEM_gworkbench "Open On Workbench"

   The graphics window will open on the Workbench instead of its
   own custom screen.
@endnode

@node ITEM_coloropt "Color Options"

   Allows setting of the following items:
   
   - Lock Colors: Don't allow the host to change the colors
   - Mask Colors: Graphics will only be written to the bitplanes 
                  needed, leaving other bitplanes untouched.
   - Erase Mask:  Bits in this mask indicate which bitplanes to 
                  clear when the screen is cleared.

   - Map color .. to: Allows one to rearrange the color mapping.
@endnode

@node ITEM_gscrclose "Close Screen"

   Close the graphics window and/or screen.
@endnode

@node ITEM_emul "Tek Emulation"

   Select Tektronix 4010/4014 or Tektronix 4105/4107 emulation.
@endnode

@node ITEM_gin "GIN Report Style"

   Select Graphics INput mode. 4010 is standard, some devices allow
   the extended mode.
@endnode

@node ITEM_eol "Report EOL String"

   Select the characters sent to indicate the End-of-report.
@endnode

@node ITEM_byp "Bypass Cancel Character"

   Select the characters that terminate Bypass mode.
@endnode

@node ITEM_mousech "Set Mouse Report Character"

   Select the character sent when clicking the mouse in Graphics INput
   mode. Usually a space - note that the requester may seem to have an
   empty string, but it may really have a space character.
@endnode

@node ITEM_incr "Incremental Mode Step"

   Select whether in incremental mode a step is in the 1024 pixel or
   in the 4096 pixel coordinate system.
@endnode

@node ITEM_gdisp "Set Display ..."

   A requester asks for the width, height left edge and top edge of the
   actual plotting area in the graphics window.
@endnode

@node ITEM_sw "Switch Screens"

   When selected, these escape sequences normally cause VLT to redisplay
   the main VLT screen when the Graphics screen is currently shown,
   and other escape sequences, when selected, cause the reverse.
@endnode

@node ITEM_sf "Use Duplex Stroke Font"

   The Duplex stroke font is prettier than the simplex stroke font, but
   takes longer to draw. You can choose to never use it or to use it in
   Zoom mode. (It is anyway only useful when the fonts are large enough).
@endnode

@node ITEM_greset "Reset Default Parameters"

   Allows one to return the graphics window's settings to either the
   previously saved ones or the "factory-preset" ones.
@endnode

@node ITEM_gsaveconf "Save Tek Configuration"

   Save the current configuration of the Graphics window to the current
   configuration file (usually s/TekPrefs.dat).
@endnode

@node ITEM_gsaveconfas "Save Tek Configuration As"

   Save the current configuration of the Graphics window to a new
   configuration file. A requester will ask for the file name.
@endnode

@node ITEM_retalpha "Return to Alpha-Numeric"

   Switches VLT back so that the main VLT screen/window is the
   active screen/window.
@endnode

@node VLT_SCRIPT "Scripting language"

   VLT native scripts are files usually ending in a .scp extension that
   contain only VLT script commands and @{"comments" link cmd_comments}. VLT ARexx scripts are
   files written in the Amiga REXX (ARexx) language, that send some 
   VLT script commands or sets (delimited by semicolons) of them to 
   VLT. The extension of these files is usually .vlt or .rexx.

   VLT's scripting language is described in detail in the printed manual.
   The information in this guide is for quick reference; all entries will
   tell you what the command does as briefly as possible. Some commands
   are described more fully in the printed manual.
   
   In this description, we will use the following conventions. Most
   commands can be @{"abbreviated" link cmd_abbreviations}. Some commands take @{"timeouts" link cmd_timeouts} as one
   of their arguments. Other commands allow a @{"VLT action string" link cmd_action} to 
   be specified. In strings VLT usually parses for @{"ARP-style escape" link cmd_ARP}
   sequences, though VLT no longer uses arp.library. Many commands
   are @{"switches" link cmd_yot}. See also the subjects: @{"string delimiters" link cmd_quotes},
   @{"use of semi-colons" link cmd_semis}, and @{"labels" link cmd_colons}.


   @{" Script command reference " link cmds_alpha}
@endnode

@node cmds_alpha "Script commands, alphabetical listing"

   @{" @                    " link cmd_execute             }  @{" execute              " link cmd_execute             }  @{" preloadgraphics      " link cmd_preloadgraphics     }
   @{" activate             " link cmd_activate            }  @{" exit                 " link cmd_exit                }  @{" prescroll            " link cmd_prescroll           }
   @{" ansicolormode        " link cmd_ansicolormode       }  @{" extract              " link cmd_extract             }  @{" programmode          " link cmd_programmode         }
   @{" applicationcursor    " link cmd_applicationcursor   }  @{" fault                " link cmd_fault               }  @{" refresh              " link cmd_refresh             }
   @{" autoscreentoback     " link cmd_autoscreentoback    }  @{" fifo                 " link cmd_fifo                }  @{" rendermode           " link cmd_rendermode          }
   @{" baud                 " link cmd_baud                }  @{" file                 " link cmd_file                }  @{" review               " link cmd_review              }
   @{" beep                 " link cmd_beep                }  @{" font                 " link cmd_font                }  @{" rexxportname         " link cmd_rexxportname        }
   @{" beepfunction         " link cmd_beepfunction        }  @{" function             " link cmd_function            }  @{" rx                   " link cmd_rx                  }
   @{" break                " link cmd_break               }  @{" goto                 " link cmd_goto                }  @{" schedule             " link cmd_schedule            }
   @{" breaktime            " link cmd_breaktime           }  @{" graphicslock         " link cmd_graphicslock        }  @{" screendepth          " link cmd_screendepth         }
   @{" buffersize           " link cmd_buffersize          }  @{" handshake            " link cmd_handshake           }  @{" screengadgets        " link cmd_screengadgets       }
   @{" cancel               " link cmd_cancel              }  @{" hangup               " link cmd_hangup              }  @{" send                 " link cmd_send                }
   @{" capture              " link cmd_capture             }  @{" helpkeylf            " link cmd_helpkeylf           }  @{" sendlinefeeds        " link cmd_sendlinefeeds       }
   @{" cd                   " link cmd_cd                  }  @{" if                   " link cmd_if                  }  @{" serialdevice         " link cmd_serialdevice        }
   @{" checkserialerror     " link cmd_checkserialerror    }  @{" interlace            " link cmd_interlace           }  @{" shifttabesctab       " link cmd_shifttabesctab      }
   @{" clear                " link cmd_clear               }  @{" kermit               " link cmd_kermit              }  @{" stripbit8            " link cmd_stripbit8           }
   @{" color                " link cmd_color               }  @{" keymap               " link cmd_keymap              }  @{" swapbackspacedelete  " link cmd_swapbackspacedelete }
   @{" columns              " link cmd_columns             }  @{" keyrepeat            " link cmd_keyrepeat           }  @{" tektronix            " link cmd_tektronix           }
   @{" configuration        " link cmd_configuration       }  @{" keyscriptcharacter   " link cmd_keyscriptcharacter  }  @{" titlebar             " link cmd_titlebar            }
   @{" console              " link cmd_console             }  @{" lines                " link cmd_lines               }  @{" trace                " link cmd_trace               }
   @{" continue             " link cmd_continue            }  @{" local                " link cmd_local               }  @{" transfer             " link cmd_transfer            }
   @{" cursorheight         " link cmd_cursorheight        }  @{" menu                 " link cmd_menu                }  @{" trap                 " link cmd_trap                }
   @{" customscreen         " link cmd_customscreen        }  @{" message              " link cmd_message             }  @{" volume               " link cmd_volume              }
   @{" delay                " link cmd_delay               }  @{" miscflags            " link cmd_miscflags           }  @{" wait                 " link cmd_wait                }
   @{" destructivebackspace " link cmd_destructivebackspace}  @{" mousesupport         " link cmd_mousesupport        }  @{" wedge                " link cmd_wedge               }
   @{" displaycrascrlf      " link cmd_displaycrascrlf     }  @{" movecursor           " link cmd_movecursor          }  @{" window               " link cmd_window              }
   @{" displaylfascrlf      " link cmd_displaylfascrlf     }  @{" numerickeypad        " link cmd_numerickeypad       }  @{" workbenchcolors      " link cmd_workbenchcolors     }
   @{" dsr                  " link cmd_dsr                 }  @{" on                   " link cmd_on                  }  @{" wrap                 " link cmd_wrap                }
   @{" echo                 " link cmd_echo                }  @{" parity               " link cmd_parity              }  @{" xmodemmode           " link cmd_xmodemmode          }
   @{" echolinefeeds        " link cmd_echolinefeeds       }  @{" paste                " link cmd_paste               }  @{" xpr                  " link cmd_xpr                 }
   @{" emit                 " link cmd_emit                }  @{" pause                " link cmd_pause               }
@endnode

@node cmd_quotes "String delimiters"

   String delimiters surround a string and tell VLT that it is dealing
   with a string instead of a command. Delimiters can be double quotes
   ", single quotes ', curly braces {}, pointed brackets <>, square
   brackets [], or parentheses ().

   Delimiters are also used in conjunction with certain commands, such as
   the "schedule" command. On the whole, anywhere that double or single
   quotes are used, the other delimiters can be used also.

   The combinations >>, }} ]] or )) act as a "universal quote". If one of
   these combinations, (without corresponding open brackets) is placed in
   a line, all text from there to the end of the line will be treated as a
   string and any reserved symbols will be ignored by VLT's script parser,
   including quotes etc. which would otherwise have been processed.
   This is particularly valuable when you want VLT to send text without
   processing it first.

   For example, if you're reading text in and then having VLT send it, you
   may run into problems, because you won't know if the text contains
   reserved symbols. So you would issue the "send" command as follows

      "send >>" sometext

   This syntax is only valid as of VLT version 5.045.
@endnode

@node cmd_semis "Use of semi-colons"

   Whenever a set of commands are written on the same line, they must be
   separated by semicolons. The semicolons tell VLT that a new command is
   beginning and an old command is ending. Writing each command on a new
   line serves the same purpose, but it may sometimes be necessary to write
   commands on the same line, for example when you are running a script
   from the VLT console window.
@endnode

@node cmd_colons "Labels"

   A name, followed by a colon, tells VLT to consider the name a label.
   Labels are used as targets for the @{"goto" link cmd_goto} command.

   The first label in a script is also the name of the script. If the
   label starts with a $ sign, then the script is a "system script", and
   it cannot be interrupted by any general script-canceling mechanism,
   short of exiting VLT. Such scripts still can be canceled by referring
   to its name explicitly. See the @{"cancel" link cmd_cancel} command and the
   corresponding menu item.
@endnode

@node cmd_comments "Script language comments"

   Whenever text in a script is prefaced by a # character, VLT ignores it.
   This is because the # character tells VLT that what follows is a
   comment, meant for the benefit of the user.

   If a comment runs over several lines, each line must be preceded by a #
   character.
@endnode

@node cmd_Abbreviations "Script command abbreviations"

   The capitalized letters (unless indicated otherwise) indicate the
   minimum number of characters that need to be specified.
   Usually, commands less than 6 characters in length need to be
   specified fully, whereas with longer commands a suitable abbreviation
   is used.
@endnode

@node cmd_Timeouts "Timeout specifications"

      hh:mm:ss.xx

   Timeouts are specified in hours, minutes, seconds and hundredths of
   seconds. Units not required need not be specified, i.e., the single
   digit 1 means one second, whereas 1:00 means one minute, etc.
@endnode

@node cmd_Action "VLT action strings"

   A VLT action string is either a string that is sent to the host
   after @{"ARP style escapes" link cmd_ARP} are parsed, or a @{"keyscript character" link cmd_keyscript}
   followed by one or more VLT script commands.
@endnode

@node cmd_keyscript "The Keyscript Character"

   When a set of script commands are issued from the VLT Console window,
   from the program for any function key, or from the program for any
   other programmable item, they must be prefaced by the VLT keyscript
   character.

   By default, this character is the tilde, ~.
   Although you can choose a different keyscript character, we advise
   against this, as it may lead to confusion.
@endnode

@node cmd_ARP "ARP-style escape sequences"

   Some commands, such as send and emit, have a text string as their
   argument. Most of the time, you can use ARP escape sequences to
   insert special characters in such strings.

   All ARP escape sequences must be preceded by the escape character,
   which, by default, is the * (asterisk).

   You can, however, choose a different escape character using the
   command environment variable called ESCAPE, or using the +e command
   line option of VLT.

   The escape sequences are as follows:

   *N    new line
   *T    horizontal tab
   *V    vertical tab
   *B    backspace
   *R    carriage return
   *F    form feed
   *E    escape (ascii 27 decimal)
   *Xnn  the character represented by the hexadecimal value nn.

   A * followed by any other character is just replaced by that character.
   In particular, if you need a * itself, then ** will translate to a 
   single *.
@endnode

@node cmd_yot "Switch commands"

      somecommand <switch>

   The syntax of the <switch> option is:

      {ON | Yes | 1 | OFf | No | 0 | Toggle}
    
   You'll see this argument description many times next to a main command
   in the list of VLT script commands below. What this means is that typing
   the main command plus On, Yes, or 1 will tell VLT to turn the option
   specified by the main command on, while typing the main command plus Off,
   No, or 0, will tell VLT to turn that option off. Typing the main command
   plus Toggle will allow you to toggle the option specified by the main
   command to its opposite state.
@endnode

@node cmd_execute "@, Execute"

      @<VLT/ARexx script name>

   or

      execute <VLT/ARexx script name>

   Can be used to execute .scp files as VLT native scripts, or to launch
   .vlt and .rexx} scripts as ARexx programs.


      @@<ARexx script name>

   Same, except the ARexx script is sent to the AREXX port and will therefore
   run asynchronously.
@endnode

@node cmd_activate "Activate"

      ACTivate {Vt100 | Tektronix | Next}

   Brings either the VT100 screen, the Tektronix screen, or the next
   screen in the screen list to the front. If the VT100 screen is not open,
   and Activate Vt100 or Activate Tektronix is received, the screen will be
   opened.
@endnode

@node cmd_ansicolormode "Ansicolormode"

      ANSicolormode @{"<switch>" link cmd_yot}  

   Switches ANSI color mode on or off.
   In ANSI color mode, color escape sequences for foreground and background
   colors are recognized.

   Note: this commands is obsolete and no longer has any effect! See also
   the @{"miscflags" link cmd_miscflags} command.
@endnode

@node cmd_applicationcursor "Applicationcursor"

      APPlicationcursor @{"<switch>" link cmd_yot}  

   Switches Application Cursor mode on or off.
@endnode

@node cmd_autoscreentoback "Autoscreentoback"

      AUToscreentoback @{"<switch>" link cmd_yot}  

   Switches Automatic Screen-to-back mode on or off.
   When set to be on, this option causes the screen to be put behind all other
   screens when a file transfer starts, with the file transfer status window
   appearing on the Workbench. Otherwise, the status window remains on VLT's
   screen, and VLT's screen remains where it is.
@endnode

@node cmd_baud "Baud"

      BAUD <baudrate> | MIDI [<new-value>]

   Lets you select a new data transmission speed.
   Valid values are 110, 300, 1200, 2400, 4800, 9600, 19200, 38400, 57600,
   115200 and Midi.

   The Midi setting is programmable; by issuing the command

      baud midi <new-value>

   where new-value is the serial speed you would like to use, you can equate
   the Midi setting with any baud rate, no matter how unusual. For instance,
   you could set Midi to the 600 bps rate used by X10 controllers. Midi is set
   by default to be 31250 bps. Note that the new Midi value is  not saved in
   the configuration file and is not extractable using the  extract command.
   Midi's programmability is provided strictly for peculiar situations.
@endnode

@node cmd_beep "Beep"

      BEEP

   Causes a beep.
   When a "Beep function" has been set, this function is executed.
   Otherwise, when the volume is set to 0, the screen will flash. If the volume
   is not zero, the built-in beep is sounded.
@endnode

@node cmd_beepfunction "Beepfunction"

      BEEPFunction <beep function>

   Lets you specify the command to be executed in place of sounding the VLT
   bell. The command is a standard @{"VLT action string" link cmd_action}. A common action string
   is:

      ~rx "address 'PingServer' beep"

   which causes the  beep command to be sent to the PingServer. See the
   documentation for the @{"PingServer" link PINGSERVER} program.
@endnode

@node cmd_break "Break"

      BREAK

   Sends a break signal to the host.
@endnode

@node cmd_breaktime "Breaktime"

      BREAKTime <break time>

   Sets the time (in microseconds) that the break signal lasts.
   The default is 75000.
@endnode

@node cmd_buffersize "Buffersize"

      buffersize [serial] <n>

   Sets the size of the serial buffer; the default is 2048 bytes, the lower
   limit is 128 bytes, and the upper limit is 8192 bytes.

      buffersize stdio <n>

   Set stdio buffer size.

      buffersize xprfast <n>

   Set fast xpr routine buffer size (see @{"miscflags" link cmd_miscflags} command).
@endnode

@node cmd_cancel "Cancel"

      CANcel {ALL | <script name> [<cancelflag>]}

   Cancels a specified script, or all scripts except the current one if all is
   specified. If a script needs to be run without interference from other
   scripts, a "cancel all" command may be placed as the first command in a
   script.

   Script names are determined by their first label. Therefore, it is
   recommended to specify the name of the script in the form of a label at
   the beginning of the script. When two scripts of the same name are present,
   the first script found will be canceled.

   If cancel is called with a scriptname and cancelflag specified, and if the
   script to be canceled was run from an ARexx context, then, when the script
   is canceled, the ARexx context will now have a value assigned to
   VLT.CANCELFLAG equal to the cancelflag that you specified. This allows you
   to use scripts which sit around indefinitely and can be canceled by
   various other scripts. By using the cancelflag, you can then tell which
   program canceled the indefinitely running script.

   For an example of how the cancelflag is used, see VLTPhoneDial.rexx.
@endnode

@node cmd_capture "Capture"

      CAPture [VERBOSE] [APPEND] <file name>

   Captures the session to a file with the specified file name. If the
   VERBOSE option is specified, any errors that may occur will be displayed
   in the message window. If APPEND is specified and the file already exists,
   then the text captured will be appended to that file.

      CAPture RAW @{"<switch>" link cmd_yot}  

   Select the capture mode.
   With "raw" mode on, all characters are captured as received, including
   carriage returns, line feeds and nulls. Otherwise, nulls are stripped out,
   and files are stored with linefeeds as line delimiters, according to Amiga
   standards.

      CAPture {SUSPEND | RESUME | FLUSH | OFF}}

   Capture Suspend and Capture Resume suspend or resume capturing to the
   current capture file. Capture Flush causes the current buffer to be
   flushed to the capture file. Capture Off causes the current capture file
   to be closed.
@endnode

@node cmd_cd "CD"

      CD <directory specification>

   Changes the directory out of which VLT is operating according to your
   specification.
@endnode

@node cmd_checkserialerror "Checkserialerror"

      CHeckserialerror { SERialdevicebusy | BAUdratemismatch |
                         LINEerror | PARityerror | BUFferoverflow |
                         NODsr | BREakreceived | ON | OFF |
                         DECimal <error mask>                       }

   Tells VLT to check for various errors. Any number of the options may be
   used in the same call. Each option specified will be switched by default
   to the ON state; to turn an option off, preface it by the OFF option.
   You can use the ON and OFF switches several times in the same command, for
   example:

      ch ser off bau on line par off buf nod

   Once you've used the OFF switch, all options specified will be switched
   OFF until you use the ON switch again, at which point all options
   specified will be switched ON. The  DECimal option can be used in
   conjunction with the "extract" command for  checkserialerror. The "extract"
   command returns a bit mask of the current state of each option. A bit mask
   in the identical format can be used to set the options in the
   checkserialerror command using the DECimal option.
@endnode

@node cmd_clear "Clear"

      CLEAR [CLOSE]

   Clear the VT100 screen. If the CLOSE option is specified, the screen or
   window will also be closed (see @{"ACTivate" link cmd_activate} and @{"window" link cmd_window}).
@endnode

@node cmd_color "Color"

      COLOR <color register> <color value> [<pen assignment>...]

   Sets a certain color register to a particular RGB value.
   For example,

      color 2 FFF

   sets color 2 to white. The three  hexadecimal digits specify Red, Green
   and Blue respectively; F means "as much R/G/B as possible" while 0 means
   "no R/G/B at all."

   When running with a custom screen in AmigaDOS 2.0 the specified color
   may also be assigned to any of the following 8 pens: DETail, BLOck, TEXt,
   SHIne, SHAdow, HIFILL, HIFILLText, BACkground, BARDetailpen, BARBlockpen,
   and BARTrimpen.

   These assignments only affect VLT when the screen has four or more colors.
   You must close VLT's screen and reopen it in order to see the full effect
   of these assignments. The Shine and Shadow assignments are also used to
   determine shadowing of all gadgets VLT uses. Since these assignments are
   not protected in any way, it is up to the user to be very careful: system
   gadgets and window borders may seem to disappear if certain pen assignments
   are made. In order to get the same colors and settings that are in effect
   on the Workbench, run the following script:

      #
      #  Set VLT's custom screen up for WB colors.
      #
      COLOR 0 AAA DETAIL BACKGROUND
      COLOR 1 000 BLOCK TEXT SHADOW HIFILLTEXT
      COLOR 2 FFF SHINE
      COLOR 3 57A HIFILL
      CLEAR CLOSE
      ACTIVATE VT

   To get pretty good looking shadowing on VLT's screen using VLT's
   default colors, use

      #
      #  Set VLT's custom screen up for default 8 colors.
      #
      COLOR 0 000 DETAIL BACKGROUND HIFILLTEXT
      COLOR 1 078 BLOCK TEXT
      COLOR 2 A00 HIFILL
      COLOR 3 090
      COLOR 4 C6A
      COLOR 5 E90
      COLOR 6 056 SHADOW
      COLOR 7 999 SHINE
      CLEAR CLOSE
      ACTIVATE VT

   As it turns out, these settings also work pretty well in 4 colors,
   although the shine pen now effectively will be color 3, and the
   shadow pen color 2. As said before, for a two-color screen these
   settings have no effect.

      COLOR REQuest

   Causes the VLT color requester to open on VLT's screen.
   The command will only return when the user has completed his
   color selection.
@endnode

@node cmd_columns "Columns"

      COLUmns <number of columns>

   Sets the number of columns to be displayed on the screen. If the number
   is larger than the number that fits on the current screen size, the font
   may be changed to a smaller size.
@endnode

@node cmd_configuration "Configuration"

      CONFiguration SAVE [<filename>]

   Allows you to save VLT's configuration, as do the "Save Configuration" and
   "Save Configuration As" options in the VLT Menu. The configuration file
   will be saved according to VLT's path search methods. If the filename is
   not specified, the file will be saved over the last read preferences file.
   If the filename is specified, the configuration file will be saved with
   that name; if no directory is specified for this file, the path will be
   searched for the file. If VLT still can't find the specified file, it will
   create that file in the current directory.
@endnode

@node cmd_continue "Continue"

      CONTinue

   Tells VLT to continue a script that is currently in a "pause," "delay,"
   or "wait" state. Execution of the script is resumed at the script command
   following the "pause", "delay", or "wait" command.

   The  CONTinue command can also be used with the name of another schedule
   as an argument. This ability to continue one schedule from inside another
   allows you to synchronize schedules. For example, consider two schedules,
   schedule A and schedule B. Schedule A consists of the following commands:

      #
      #  ScheduleA.scp
      #
      A:      # First label = name of script: A
      @ScheduleB.scp
      pause
      ...     # miscellaneous commands

   while Schedule B looks like this:

      #
      #  ScheduleB.scp
      #
      B:
      ...     # miscellaneous commands
      continue A
      exit quiet

   After starting schedule B, schedule A would normally continue without any
   regard to Schedule B's further behavior, but since A encounters the "pause"
   command, it waits. Meanwhile, schedule B executes what it needs to execute,
   then uses the  continue A command, which breaks A out of the "pause" state
   and allows it to execute the rest of its commands. While Schedule A
   continues to execute, Schedule B exits.
@endnode

@node cmd_console "Console"

      CONSole {Open | Close |
               Specification <console string> | Height <height>}

   Specified with "open", opens the console window; with "close", closes the
   console window. The "specification" suboption lets you specify the console
   string, while the  height suboption lets you specify the amount of space
   left between the bottom of the text above the console window and the
   bottom of the screen.

   In VLT versions before 5.517, a command called "CONSolewindowadjust"
   existed. This command was removed.

   If you don't want VLT to change the text display just because there is a
   console, then specify a console height of 0. The console height that you
   set with this command does not actually affect the size of the console
   window. It only specifies how much room to leave at the bottom for a
   console (or whatever else). The default is 55 pixels.
@endnode

@node cmd_cursorheight "Cursorheight"

      CURsorheight  <height>

   Specifies the height of the cursor.
   If the height specified is larger than eight, the cursor height will adapt
   to any font changes.
@endnode

@node cmd_customscreen "Customscreen"

      CUStomscreen [Mode <modeid>] [Width <width>] [Height <height>]
                   [OVerscan <overscan>] [Autoscroll <autoscroll>]
                   [Depth <depth>]

   Most of these options will force VLT to open a custom screen. The
   overscan clip rect is specified as a number between 1 and 4. When 
   <autoscroll> is non-zero, autoscroll will be enabled, otherwise disabled.

   For compatibility, VLT will also continue to recognize the old syntax
   which only provided switching capability between Workbench use and 
   custom screen mode:

      CUStomscreen @{"<switch>" link cmd_yot}
@endnode

@node cmd_delay "Delay"

      DELAY @{"<timeout>" link cmd_timeouts}

   Causes the script to pause for the specified amount of time.
@endnode

@node cmd_destructivebackspace "Destructivebackspace"

      DESTructivebackspace @{"<switch>" link cmd_yot}  

   When "DESTructivebackspace" is set to be on, the backspace key causes
   the cursor to erase text as it moves backwards.
@endnode

@node cmd_displaycrascrlf "Displaycrascrlf"

      DISPLAYCrascrlf @{"<switch>" link cmd_yot}  

   Behaves just like the "Display CR as CR/LF" option of the Communications
   Menu.
@endnode

@node cmd_displaylfascrlf "Displaylfascrlf"

      DISPLAYLfascrlf @{"<switch>" link cmd_yot}  

   Behaves just like the "Display LF as CR/LF" option of the Communications
   Menu.
@endnode

@node cmd_dsr "Dsr"

      DSR <number> <device status report string>

   Chooses the primary (number = 1) or secondary (number = 2) device status
   report string.
@endnode

@node cmd_echo "Echo"

      ECHO @{"<switch>" link cmd_yot}  

   Lets you switch echo on or off.
@endnode

@node cmd_echolinefeeds "Echolinefeeds"

      ECHOLinefeeds @{"<switch>" link cmd_yot}  

   When on, the "ECHOLinefeeds" option causes linefeeds to be echoed to the
   screen as well as carriage returns, when the return key is pressed in local
   echo mode.
@endnode

@node cmd_emit "Emit"

      EMIT [RAW] <character string>

   Tells VLT to display a character string on the screen at the
   current cursor position. If the RAW option is specified, the string is not
   parsed for @{"ARP style escape" link cmd_ARP} sequences.
@endnode

@node cmd_exit "Exit"

      EXIT [{VLT | [QUiet] [<next script>]}]

   Lets you exit the current script, or quit out of VLT entirely if VLT is
   specified. When exiting a script, a message is displayed to indicate
   that the script has terminated, unless the  quiet option is specified.
   If a next script is specified, that script will then be executed.
@endnode

@node cmd_extract "Extract"

      EXTRact [<field name>]

   In this form, the command is available from ARexx only.
   It extracts information from VLT in the form of the VLT. stem variable.
   If no field is specified, all fields are extracted. The script called
   ExtractTest.rexx (run from a shell) will display all information that
   can be extracted from VLT.

   The extract command also has an optional second argument.

      extract <item> <portname>

   When given, the value of the item(s) is sent to the ARexx message port
   with name <portname> as arg0 of the ARexx message in the form:

      <item> = <value>

   In this form, the extract command can also be used outside of an ARexx
   context.
@endnode

@node cmd_fault "Fault"

      FAULT <error number>

   This command is available only from ARexx.
   It reads the error number specified and puts the corresponding text
   explanation in the variable VLT.Error. All VLT commands set the RC
   (error code number) variable in an ARexx script to a code depending on
   whether a command was successful or not. One may call the "Fault" command
   with RC as an argument to find out what the error code meant.
@endnode

@node cmd_fifo "Fifo"

      FIFO @{"<switch>" link cmd_yot}

   Turns Fifo Pipes on or off.
@endnode

@node cmd_file "File"

      FILE {SENd | RECeive | GET} [<file name>]

   Lets you send or receive the file with the specified file name to or from
   the host using the currently active transfer protocol.
@endnode

@node cmd_font "Font"

      FONT [{LARge | NORmal | SMall | SCreen | MOnospaced}] [SIZE <n>] <name>

   Used to change VLT's fonts. See also the corresponding menu item.
   The defaults are "normal" and size 8. Note that setting the screen font
   from a script does *not* close the screen and reopen it automatically.
@endnode

@node cmd_function "Function"

      Function <key number> <command>

   Set function key indicated by the key number to a command. Key numbers are
   in the range 1 to 128, where

      1   - 10  are the regular unshifted function keys
      11  - 20  are the shifted function keys
      21  - 30  are the ctrl-ed function keys
      31  - 40  are the alt-ed function keys
      41  - 50  are the menu items right-Amiga 1 through 0
      51  - 80  are the screen gadgets
      81  - 90  are the alt-ed keypad keys 0 - 9
      91  & 115 are the alt-ed and shift-alt-ed keypad Enter
      92  & 116 are the alt-ed and shift-alt-ed keypad -
      93  & 117 are the alt-ed and shift-alt-ed keypad (
      94  & 118 are the alt-ed and shift-alt-ed keypad )
      95  & 119 are the alt-ed and shift-alt-ed keypad /
      96  & 120 are the alt-ed and shift-alt-ed keypad *
      97  & 121 are the alt-ed and shift-alt-ed keypad + or Help
                (Only true if the "HelpKeyLF" option hasn't been used to
                set the Help key to the linefeed character.)
      98  & 122 are the alt-ed and shift-alt-ed keypad .
      99  & 123 are the alt-ed and shift-alt-ed up arrow
      100 & 124 are the alt-ed and shift-alt-ed down arrow
      101 & 125 are the alt-ed and shift-alt-ed right arrow
      102 & 126 are the alt-ed and shift-alt-ed left arrow
      103 & 127 are the alt-ed and shift-alt-ed Delete
      104 & 128 are the alt-ed and shift-alt-ed Help
      105 - 114 are the shift-alt-ed keypad keys 0 - 9.

   The command takes the usual form of a @{"VLT-action-string" link cmd_action}.
@endnode

@node cmd_goto "Goto"

      GOTO <label-name>

   Tells VLT to "goto" a specified label (a name with a colon after it)
   and execute all the commands after that label. The label name should
   be specified without the trailing colon when used with the "goto"
   command, even though, when used as a label elsewhere in the program,
   it  must have the trailing colon.
@endnode

@node cmd_graphicslock "Graphicslock"

      GRAphicslock @{"<switch>" link cmd_yot}  

   Switches graphics lock on or off.
   When on, special characters from the host will not be able to switch you
   from the text screen to the graphics screen. Otherwise, certain control
   characters and escape sequences can change VLT's mode to the graphics mode.
   This script command corresponds to the "Lock Graphics" command found in
   the Graphics Menu of the text screen and in the Control Menu of the
   graphics screen.
@endnode

@node cmd_handshake "Handshake"

      HANDshake {None | Xon/xoff | 7-wire} [{Xon/xoff | 7-wire | cts/rts}]

   Lets you specify the handshake mode for the serial port.
   In case both Xon/Xoff and 7Wire are desired, both options may be specified.
   In addition, the keyword CTS/RTS can be substituted for the 7Wire option.
@endnode

@node cmd_hangup "Hangup"

      HANGup

   Causes a "hangup."
   This is accomplished by dropping the DTR signal on the serial port for a
   period of 1 second. Notice that most modems can be set to ignore the DTR
   status, and that three-wire cables do not usually convey this signal to
   the modem. If this option does not work, you may have to send a special
   command sequence to your modem, such as +++ followed by a delay and "ATH"
   in the case of Hayes compatible modems.
@endnode

@node cmd_helpkeylf "Helpkeylf"

      HELpkeylf @{"<switch>" link cmd_yot}  

   When you turn  HELpkeylf on using this script command, the help key
   transmits the line feed character (ctrl-J) to the host. Otherwise, the
   help key transmits the sequence <esc>O l (lower case L) when in application
   keypad mode.
@endnode

@node cmd_if "If"

      IF [NOT] <condition> <command string> [else <command string>]

   This command is comparable to the if...then flow control statements of
   high-level programming languages. The IF recognizes a specific set of
   conditions listed below. It also recognizes their negatives, specified
   using the "not" option.

   If the condition is met, the command string included afterwards is
   executed as if a "schedule" command was used. If the condition is not met,
   nothing happens and no error message is returned, unless you have
   specified another course of action using an else clause.

   Condition           | True if:
   --------------------+-------------------------------------------------
   Tektronix           | VLT is in Tektronix mode.
   VT100               | VLT is in VT100 mode.
   ECho                | Local Echo is currently.
   NUMerickeypad       | Keypad is currently in numeric mode.
   APPlicationcursor   | Cursor keys are currently in application mode.
   SWApbackspacedelete | Backspace and delete keys are swapped.
   HELpkeylf           | Help key is set to send a linefeed.
   SHIfttabesc         | Shift-Tab sends both a tab and an escape character.
   LOCal               | VLT is in local mode, i.e. keystrokes are not sent
                       | to the host.
   ECHOLinefeeds       | Return key, when pressed, echos a carriage return
                       | and linefeed.
   SENDLinefeeds       | Return key, when pressed, sends a carriage return
                       | and linefeed.
   CLIP                | VLT currently has something in its clipboard buffer.
   SECONDcursor        | Secondary cursor is currently displayed.
   SELECTdown          | Left mouse button is currently pressed down.


   This command is for example useful when you want to program keys to behave
   differently in Alphanumeric (VT100) and Graphics (Tektronix) mode.

   The commands execute on the same schedule that the "if" command was
   called from, so you can include "goto"'s that refer to labels outside the
   "if"'s command string, as well as "exit" commands, and have them work
   correctly. Unlike in VT versions previous to version 5.517, all the
   commands within the if statement execute synchronously with the schedule
   in which the if appears.

   For example:

      if VT100 (emit "Avalon"; delay 1; emit "Arthur"); emit "done"

   If VLT is currently in VT100 mode, then  Avalon will appear,
   followed, after a delay of one second, by  Arthur;  done
   will appear immediately afterwards.
   Previous to VLT 5.517, because the commands within the if were executed
   asynchronously, Avalon would appear, followed immediately by done, and
   Arthur would appear a second later.
@endnode

@node cmd_interlace "Interlace"

      INTerlace @{"<switch>" link cmd_yot}

   Lets you switch interlace on or off, for custom screens.
   This command is now obsolete. See the @{"customscreen" link cmd_customscreen} command.
@endnode

@node cmd_kermit "Kermit"

      KERmit BYE

   Sends a `Bye' message to host, if the Kermit protocol is currently selected.

      KERmit DOWncase @{"<switch>" link cmd_yot}  

   Calling this option with either the YES, ON, or 1 subcommand causes the
   names of received files to be converted to lower case.

      KERmit FINish

   Behaves like  KERmit BYE, except that it does not log you off the host.

      KERmit PACKetsize <packet size>

   Sets maximum packet size to be used for Kermit transfers.

      KERmit MODE {Hostserver | Sendreceive}

   Lets you select Kermit's transfer mode; your choices are "host is server"
   or regular send/receive.
@endnode

@node cmd_keymap "Keymap"

      KEYMap <keymap name>

   Lets you select a different special keymap.
@endnode

@node cmd_keyrepeat "Keyrepeat"

      KEYRepeat @{"<switch>" link cmd_yot}

   Lets you switch key repeat mode on or off. When key repeat is on, most keys
   pressed and held will send characters repeatedly. When not set, keys will
   never repeat.
@endnode

@node cmd_keyscriptcharacter "Keyscriptcharacter"

      KEYScriptcharacter <ASCII character number>

   Allows you to select the keyscript character.
   By default, this is the ANSI character tilde, ~, ASCII number 126.
   Since many scripts assume the keyscript character to be a tilde,
   it is usually unwise to change it.
@endnode

@node cmd_lines "Lines"

      LINES <number of lines>

   Changes the number of lines to be displayed on the screen to the
   number indicated. If necessary/possible, the font will be changed to
   a smaller or larger size.
@endnode

@node cmd_local "Local"

      LOCAL @{"<switch>" link cmd_yot}  

   Sets VLT to operate in  local mode, which means that characters typed
   on the keyboard are not sent on to the host. Note that text sent by
   other means does get sent to the host (i.e. text sent from the console,
   pasted from the Review Buffer, or sent from scripts).
@endnode

@node cmd_menu "Menu"

      MENU <menunum> <itemnum> [<subnum>]

   Executes specified menu item as if it had been selected from the
   main window's menus. Note that when counting items, the count starts from
   zero and the dashed separation bars used in the menus must be counted.
@endnode

@node cmd_message "Message"

      MESsage <message>

   Posts a message using VLT's message window.
   The *n escape may be used to cause line feeds. When the <message>
   is not specified, the current message window is closed. When an empty
   string is used, the message history window opens at the last message.
@endnode

@node cmd_miscflags "Miscflags"

      MISCFlags {add | remove} <option flag>

   "MISCFlags" allows you to set minor VLT options using the option flags
   listed below. Adding sets an option flag to be on, while removing sets
   an option flag to be off.

   Flag                 | Action when added
   ---------------------+------------------------------------------------
   ABUseansicolors      | use ANSI color sequences <esc>[40m and <esc>[41m
                        | in SLAC defined ways.
   ALPhaonmainscreen    | Causes Tektronix alpha mode text to appear on
                        | the VT100 screen, rather than on the Graphics
                        | screen.
   AUToactivate         | Causes the VLT screen to pop back to the front
                        | after VLT finishes uploading or downloading files.
   DISplayoff           | Prevents new data from being shown on VLT's screen.
   ECHoconsole          | Echoes lines typed in the console window to the
                        | main VLT screen.
   FAStxprio            | use double-buffered XPR IO routines. This 
                        | option may not always work correctly, and should
                        | only be used after establishing that it doesn't
                        | cause problems.
   INActivemessages     | Causes message windows to come up inactive instead
                        | of active.
   MARgins              | display left and right margins
   NOAutopens           | do not automatically assign shadow/shine and
                        | menu pens during OpenScreen.
   NODisplayescape      | Treat <esc> as a non-display character.
   NOEscapescripts      | Nullifies the escape key's ability to abort scripts.
   NOLocalprint         | Switches off the capability for automatic local
                        | printing.
   NOMessages           | Prevents VLT from displaying message windows,
                        | including the file transfer status window.
   NOOwndevunit         | turns off the support for Chris Wichura's
                        | OwnDevUnit standard for arbitrating access to
                        | serial devices.
   PADdedclips          | Sets the VLT review buffer up to pad files saved
                        | to the clipboard so that all clip files (in
                        | accordance with IFF specs) contain an even number
                        | of characters. Padding of clipboard files disagrees
                        | with some editors, so the option is by default off.
   SERialshared         | Causes VLT to open the serial port in shared mode.
                        | You must reopen the serial port before this takes
                        | effect, either by selecting the "Reset" menu option
                        | or "Hangup" option or by issuing the "HANGup" script
                        | command.
   TEKNOAnsicolors      | causes VLT to support <csi n m> sequences in 
                        | Tektronix mode, as long as n is in the range between
                        | 30 and 37.
   TEKNOBoundary        | When added, prevents panel outlines from being drawn.
   TEKNOPointer         | Affects the display of cross hairs in Tektronix mode.
                        | Normally, when cross hairs are being displayed, the
                        | mouse pointer changes to a target box on the
                        | graphics screen. When "TEKNOPointer" is added, only
                        | the cross hairs are displayed.
   UNBufferedcapture    | Capture to a file is unbuffered. This is occasionally
                        | useful when capturing to strange devices.
   VT100toprow          | When added, forces the top four keys of the numeric
                        | keypad to send VT100 sequences under all
                        | circumstances.


      MISCFlags <number>

   The old "MISCFlags" interface, for reasons of compatibility, is supported
   in addition to the newer interface discussed above.

   The old-style  MISCFlags assigns a number to each flag; any of these
   bitflags is set to be off by a value of zero; moreover, all of these
   flags are by default off. To set a bitflag to be on, add the number
   specified below after the "MISCFlags" command.

   PADdedclips            1
   DISplayoff             2
   NOMessages             4
   SERialshared           8
   TEKNOPointer           16
   UNBufferedcapture      32
   NOLocalprint           64
   ALPhaonmainscreen      256
   NOOwndevunit           512
   TEKNOAnsicolors        1024
   INActivemessages       2048
   AUToactivate           4096
   TEKNOBoundary          8192
   VT100toprow            16384
   NOEscapescripts        32768
   NOAutopens             65536
   FAStxprio              131072
   ABUseansicolors        262144
   MARgins                524288
   NODisplayescape        1048576
   ECHoconsole            2097152

   In order to set more than one bitflag to be on, add the numbers
   which set the two flags to be on and include the result after the
   MISCFlags command.
   For example, to set Bit 0 and 1 to be on, type 3 after the "MISCFlags"
   command. To set Bits 0, 1, and 2 to be on, type 7, to set Bits 1, 2, and 4
   type 22, etc.
   To reset a bitflag to off, add up the current values of the other bitflags
   and include that number after the "MISCFlags" command.
@endnode

@node cmd_mousesupport "Mousesupport"

      MOUsesupport [shift] [ctrl] [alt] [selectup] [selectdown]
                   <program string> [@{"<switch>" link cmd_yot}]

   By default, when you use this command, no qualifiers are specified
   and selectdown is implied. The program string is a @{"VLT action string" link cmd_action},
   i.e. it must start with a ~ to be interpreted as a script command.
   Otherwise, the string is interpreted as straight text to be sent,
   with the keyword "auto" being the one exception. When auto (not ~auto!)
   is specified, the mouse is programmed to send as many cursor sequences
   as it takes to get from the current cursor position to the mouse
   position.

   The switch argument is provided for backward compatibility:
   When specified as "on", the left mouse button without shift and/or ctrl
   and/or alt keys is set to "auto" for both mouse button clicks and
   releases (selectdown and selectup). When specified as "off", the same
   combination will be programmed to an empty string.
@endnode

@node cmd_movecursor "Movecursor"

      MOVecursor <x1> <y1> [<x2>] [<y2>]}

   Moves the location of the cursor to (x, y) when only the first two
   coordinates are specified. (1, 1) is the upper left-hand corner.
   The maximum values are determined by the displayed number of lines
   and columns. Note, that this command does not notify the host of the
   new cursor location.

   When at least the first three coordinates are specified, this command
   applies to the secondary cursor. The second set of coordinates are row
   and column specifications, either in absolute screen coordinates or
   relative to the text cursor; you indicate which you want used by prefacing
   the coordinate with either ABS or REL.

   The coordinates can also be specified as MOUSE, in which case that
   coordinate is set to the current X or Y position of the mouse,
   depending on which coordinate you specified in this way.

   For example, the command

      move rel 0 mouse 12 mouse

   would display the secondary cursor with the top/left corner positioned at
   the column of the current text cursor (rel 0) and at line 12. The
   bottom/right edge would be at the current mouse position. Note that the
   coordinates are sorted appropriately to disallow negative-sized cursors.
   To see this command in action, check the script @{"NeatStuff.scp" link neatstuff}.
@endnode

@node cmd_numerickeypad "Numerickeypad"

      NUMerickeypad @{"<switch>" link cmd_yot}

   Switches numeric keypad mode on or off. When set, the keypad transmits the
   characters as displayed on the key caps. Otherwise, the keypad transmits
   standard VT100 escape sequences.
@endnode

@node cmd_on "On"

      ON <character string> <command>

   Waits until the specified character string is received and then performs
   the specified command. Only a single command may be specified.
   "On" traps remain in force until the context they belong to expires.
   If another "on" trap is specified with the same character string, the new
   "on" command supersedes the old one; if an "on" command is specified with
   the same character string but an empty command string, the trap will be
   removed.
@endnode

@node cmd_parity "Parity"

      PARity <parity specification>

   Selects the parity to be used for serial port communications. Valid values
   are given by a sequence of three characters: the number of data bits
   (7 or 8), the parity mode (N, M, S, E or O), and the number of stop bits
   (1 or 2), e.g. 7E1 or 8N1.

   Alternatively, the following shortcuts may be used: None (8N1),
   Mark (7M1), Space (7S1), Even (7E1) or Odd (7O1).
@endnode

@node cmd_paste "Paste"

      PASte { CLIP | FILE <filename> | STRING <string> | CANcel} [AUTO] [EDIT]
              [PREfix <string>] [DELays <line-delay> [<character delay>]]

   The PASte command is a command, which is actually used internally by
   the Paste Menu options. It has a slew of subcommands, among them "clip",
   "file", and "string", which indicate what type of material is to be pasted.

   Using the PASte command requires a few peculiar constructions, since
   actually pasting something requires using the command in a loop, and the
   actual operation requires several steps.

   First, the contents of the clipboard, file, or string, must be loaded
   into VLT's internal paste buffer. You can accomplish this using the "clip",
   "file", or "string" options. For example, the command

      paste clip

   retrieves the Amiga clipboard contents and stuffs it into VLT's internal
   buffer. In a similar fashion, the command

      paste file work:foo/bar.txt

   tells VLT to retrieve the contents of work:foo/bar.txt and to put it in
   VLT's internal buffer, while the command

      paste string "This is a test"

   causes VLT to put the words "This is a test" into the internal buffer.

   Once we have something in the internal buffer, we need to paste it into
   VLT's input stream. The "paste" command, by itself, can only send a
   single line at most; if used with character delays, it will send only
   one character at a time.

   This is why a loop is needed to accomplish the full paste operation,
   so that your script can loop over the buffer contents until everything
   has been sent to the host.

   Such a loop can be created automatically by using the command

      paste AUTO

   which causes your program to loop until everything has been pasted.
   You can achieve the same effect by using the following code:

      $clipprog: paste clip; $1: paste; if not clip exit; goto $1

   As you can see, this clipprog script uses the "if" command; if
   anything is left in the internal buffer, the loop continues;
   otherwise the program exits.

   In this context, you can also use the "edit" subcommand. The "paste
   edit" command acts similarly to paste, except that it brings up a string
   requester which allows you to edit a line of text before it is actually
   pasted into VLT's input stream. You can also use the command "paste edit
   auto, which allows you to send an entire file, etc. to the host while
   editing it a line at a time.

   Only one paste operation can be active at a time, and you can abort a
   paste operation by issuing the command 

      paste cancel

   This command empties and deallocates the current internal buffer and
   indirectly causes any paste operation currently in progress to abort.

   The "paste" command has two more subcommands, "prefix" and "delays".
   Issuing the command "paste prefix", followed by a string, will cause
   VLT to preface whatever you are pasting with that string. For example,
   if you were sending a list of female nobility, and you wanted
   every line of the file you were pasting prefaced by
   the word "Lady", you would type

      Paste prefix "Lady"
      Paste file kingdom:nobles.txt
      Paste auto

   Issuing the command "paste delays", followed by a specified line delay
   and then (optionally) a specified character delay (in milliseconds),
   allows you to choose the amount of time VLT takes between pasting lines
   and between pasting characters. For example, the command

      paste delays 300 40

   would cause VLT to delay 300 milliseconds after pasting each line and
   40 milliseconds after pasting each character.
@endnode

@node cmd_pause "Pause"

      PAUse

   Halts execution at this point in the script and waits for a "continue"
   or "goto".
@endnode

@node cmd_preloadgraphics "Preloadgraphics"

      PRELoadgraphics @{"<switch>" link cmd_yot}

   When ON, causes VLT to open the graphics screen on startup. When
   not set, VLT only opens the graphics screen when needed.
@endnode

@node cmd_prescroll "Prescroll"

      PREScroll <number of lines>

   Sets the maximum number of lines to be prescrolled.
   If the currently available data indicates that the screen needs to be
   scrolled a number of times, all scrolls up to the maximum number set
   with this command will be performed at once. This increases scrolling
   speed.

   When a negative number is specified, then VLT will operate in smooth
   scroll mode, and the number represents the number of pixels scrolled
   for each scroll.
@endnode

@node cmd_programmode "Programmode"

      PROGrammode @{"<switch>" link cmd_yot}

   Switches program mode on or off.
@endnode

@node cmd_refresh "Refresh"

      REFresh

   Refreshes the text on the screen. Sometimes useful when running on the
   Workbench screen.
@endnode

@node cmd_rendermode "Rendermode"

      RENdermode {Quick | Color | Normal}}

   Sets the rendering mode. "Quick" means that all text will be rendered
   in monochrome mode, but very quickly, whereas "color" means that
   all text attributes will be converted to different colors, and also
   ANSI color sequences are recognized. In "Normal" mode, bold text will
   be displayed in a different color, but all VT100 text attributes are
   displayed as intended.
@endnode

@node cmd_review "Review"

      REView  <review command> [<argument>]}

   Executes a review buffer command. All commands consist of a single
   character, and some of them allow an argument. There may be white
   space between the command and the argument but there doesn't have to be.
   The allowed commands and arguments are shown in the table below.

   Command  |  Argument  | Meaning
   ---------+------------+------------------------------------------------------
   A        | <filename> | Save selected lines to filename
   B        | <size>     | Set buffer size to <size> bytes
   C        |            | Clear review buffer
   S,D,I    |            | Select, Deselect, Invert all lines
   S,D,I    | S          | Select, Deselect, Invert Search line only
   S,D,I    | T          | Select, Deselect, Invert from search line to top
   S,D,I    | B          | Select, Deselect, Invert from search line to bottom
   J        | <lines>    | Jump relative to search line by <lines> lines.
            |            | Negative numbers jump towards top
   K        | <line>     | Jump relative to <line> from top. 0 is top line;
            |            | Negative numbers count from bottom;
            |            | -1 is bottom line
   F        | <string>   | Search from top Forward for <string>.
   R        | <string>   | Search from bottom in Reverse for <string>.
   G        |            | Repeat search Forward.
   T        |            | Repeat search Reverse.
   H        | <string>   | Search from last search pos. Forward for <string>.
   Y        | <string>   | Search from last search pos. Reverse for <string>.
   M        | UL, UP, T  | Move Up Line, Up Page, toTop
   M        | DL, DP, B  | Move Down Line Down Page, to Bottom
   M        | LC, LP, LM | Move Left Column, Left Page, to Left Margin
   M        | RC, RP, RM | Move Right Column, Right Page, to Right Margin
   N        |            | Append to file
   O        |            | Open window
   P        |            | New page
   Q        |            | Update window
   V        | <filename> | Append to specified file
   W        |            | Resave to current file (overwrites existing file)
   X        | <Name>     | If previous command successful, set environment
            |            | variable <name> to current search line. Else erase
            |            | the environment variable <name>. If called from an
            |            | ARexx context, the REXX variable <Name> is set to
            |            | the current search line.
   Z        |            | Save to Clipboard
@endnode



@node cmd_rexxportname "Rexxportname"

      REXxportname <name>

   Changes the name of VLT's ARexx port to the specified name. This command
   can only be used if no outstanding ARexx scripts are around.
@endnode

@node cmd_rx "RX"

      RX [ SYNChronous ]  <ARexx command>

   Submits the specified ARexx command to ARexx.
   If the synchronous option is specified, the command is executed
   synchronously: the program will wait until the ARexx command has
   completed before continuing.
@endnode

@node cmd_schedule "Schedule"

      SCHedule <commands>

   Creates a new context and starts executing the specified commands
   in that context. Multiple commands need to be separated by semicolons.

      SCHedule FUNCTION <key number>

   Similar to "schedule"; can be used to execute the contents of
   a function key.
@endnode

@node cmd_screendepth "Screendepth"

      SCREENDepth <depth>

   Sets the depth of the screen. Values from 1 to 3 are allowed.
@endnode

@node cmd_screengadgets "Screengadgets"

      SCREENGadgets @{"<switch>" link cmd_yot}  

   Switches screen gadgets on or off.
   When on, the standard screen displays 30 gadgets at the bottom, all of
   which are programmable. The display will be adjusted to fit the set
   number of lines in the remaining area.
@endnode

@node cmd_send "Send"

      SEND [RAW]  <character string>

   Sends a string of characters to the host.
   If  raw is specified as an option, the string is not parsed for
   @{"ARP style escape" link cmd_ARP} sequences, but by default it is.
@endnode

@node cmd_sendlinefeeds "Sendlinefeeds"

      SENDLinefeeds @{"<switch>" link cmd_yot}  

   When ON, this option causes linefeeds to be transmitted in addition
   to carriage returns, whenever the return key is pressed.
@endnode

@node cmd_serialdevice "Serialdevice"

      SERialdevice {<device> [  <unit> ] | none}}

   Selects a different serial device to be used. Optionally, select the
   unit number to be used. If the unit number is not specified, the previous
   unit number is assumed. If the "none" option is specified, the current
   serial device is closed.
@endnode

@node cmd_shifttabesctab "Shifttabesctab"

      SHIfttabesctab @{"<switch>" link cmd_yot}  

   When this option is ON, the TAB key transmits <esc> <tab> to the host when
   the shift key is pressed at the same time. Some hosts interpret this
   sequence as "back tab." When not set, the shifted TAB key transmits
   just <tab>.
@endnode

@node cmd_stripbit8 "Stripbit8"

      STRipbit8 @{"<switch>" link cmd_yot}

   Switches stripping of the high-order bit of data coming in through the
   serial port on or off. This is only useful with parity settings that
   have 8 data bits.
@endnode

@node cmd_swapbackspacedelete "Swapbackspacedelete"

      SWApbackspacedelete @{"<switch>" link cmd_yot}  

   When ON, this option swaps the functions of the backspace and delete
   keys. This option is useful for example to VAX users.
@endnode

@node cmd_tektronix "Tektronix"

      TEKtronix MENU <menunum> <itemnum> [<subnum>]

   Executes the specified menu item as if it had been selected from the
   Tektronix window menus. Note that when counting items, the counting
   starts at zero and the dashed separation bars in the menus must be
   counted also.

      TEKtronix PAN [x1 [y1 [x2 [y2]]]]

   Using the arguments, specify a starting and ending point. The TEK PAN
   command will cause the ending point to wind up in the starting point's
   original location.

   If x2 and/or y2 are missing, they are set to equal x1 and/or y1.
   If x1 and/or y1 are missing, they are set to zero. The coordinates
   are in pixels, so beware!

      TEKtronix PRINT {MAXimum | SMALL | MEDIUM | FULL | LARGE}

   Behaves like the "Print Bitmap" menu option of the Graphics screen's
   Image Menu; lets you print the image currently displayed on your
   graphics screen using a printer attached to your Amiga. Each option
   allows you to print the picture in a different size: the maximum size,
   small size (one-third page), medium size (two-thirds page), large size,
   or full page size (FULL and LARGE are the same option, really).

      TEKtronix SAVEas {ILBM <filename> | POStscript <filename> |
                        BINary [<filename>] | COMmand <filename>}

   Corresponds to the various save commands in the  Image Menu. The ILBM
   option corresponds to the "Save Bitmap As IFF File" option. The 
   POStscript option corresponds to the "Save as PostScript" menu option.
   The  BINary option corresponds to the "Save As New File" and
   "Save As Current File" options: if a file is not specified, the current
   display is saved to a file opened in a previous attempt, overwriting
   that file's contents. The COMmand option corresponds to the
   "Save As Script Commands" option.

      TEKtronix ZOOM [x1 [y1 [x2 [y2]]]]

   The coordinates specify, in pixels, the upper left and lower right corner
   of the area to be zoomed in on. If x2 and/or y2 are missing, they are set
   to equal x1 and/or y1. If x1 and/or y1 are missing, they are set to zero.
   If the size of the box is zero, as it would be if ZOOM were called without
   any arguments, the action will be to zoom to full size (in other words, to
   unzoom the picture).

      TEKtronix ....

   There are several other  TEKtronix script commands available. Since they
   are rather arcane, we won't discuss them here, but you can find out what
   they are by saving a graphics file as script commands. To do this, use
   the  "Save As Script Commands" option of the Image Menu.
@endnode

@node cmd_titlebar "Titlebar"

      TITlebar @{"<switch>" link cmd_yot}  

   When this is switched on, VLT's custom screen will display a
   titlebar on both the alphanumeric screen and the Tektronix screen.
   VLT will correctly take the title bar height into account when
   calculating where to display text.
@endnode

@node cmd_trace "Trace"

      TRACE <flags> <command-delay>

   When <flags> is set to a non-zero value, certain tracing options
   are switched on. When <command-delay> is non-zero, a delay is
   inserted after each line of trace output. The delay is in ticks,
   i.e. 50 ticks is one second. The flags variable consists of a mask.

   Bit 0 enables tracing of every line in the script.

   Bit 1 enables tracing of all traps (i.e. "on"s, "wait"s and "trap"s).
   Also, little tick marks are displayed on the screen at or near the
   words that caused the trap.

   Bit 2 causes the output to be displayed in VLT's Console window (if
   it is open) or in the message window (if the console is not open).

   Bit 3 causes the output to be appended to the file VLT.log in the
   current default directory. The file is closed after each addition,
   so that in case of crash the file most often is preserved.

   Example: trace 15 20 causes both script line tracing, trap tracing, and
   the output is sent to both the console (if it is open) and to the log
   file. There will be a .4 second delay after each script line and each
   trap line.

   Note: if you suspect that a particular script may cause a crash, be
   warned that logging to VLT.log may be hazardous to your hard disk.
   Better set your default to rad:, and use DiskSalv to recover the
   file from rad: if rad: doesn't recover by itself. If a script causes
   a crash, be sure to report the problem.
@endnode

@node cmd_transfer "Transfer"

      TRANsfer Mode {image | text}

   Selects image or text mode for file transfers. In text mode, files are
   assumed to be text files, and end-of-line sequences are converted.
   Also, ctrl-Z's in the file may be used as an end-of-file indication.

      TRANsfer Protocol {Kermit | Xmodem | Ascii | Quickb | Zmodem | Ymodem}

   Selects the transfer protocol: one of Kermit, XMODEM, YMODEM, ZMODEM,
   ascii or quickb. An obsolete option is "External". This option no longer
   has any effect. See also the @{"XPR" link cmd_xpr} command.
@endnode

@node cmd_trap "Trap"

      TRAP <trap-operation>

   The trap command is the most flexible of the three trap commands. It has
   several possible subcommands.

      trap add [<trap-ID>] [<options>] <match-string> <actions>

   Adds a trap to the system. Depending on which option you specify, the
   trap will behave differently.

   A trap-ID only has to be given if the trap is to be referenced specifically
   by a later command (such as "trap activate"). Trap-ID's are integer numbers
   between zero and 32767. You may also want to use one of the <options>
   strings:

   case            Make matching of trap string with received string
                   case sensitive.
   defer           Initialize trap as inactive.
   autodeactivate  Deactivate trap after first occurrence.
   install         Install this trap permanently, which will keep it
                   alive beyond the duration of the schedule.
   wild            allow the ? wildcard in the match string - it will then
                   match any character.

   All traps must have a <match-string> string (a trap string), although the
   <match-string> may be the keyword "nothing". Traps must also have an
   <actions> string, a set of VLT commands separated by semicolons and bounded
   by string delimiters.

      trap cause <trap-ID> [<trap-ID>] ...

   Causes trap(s) with specified ID(s) to be sprung, even if the <match-string>
   has not been received.

      trap activate {<trap-ID> [<trap-ID>] ... | all}

   Causes trap(s) with specified ID(s) to be activated; this command is used
   when a trap has been deferred and you want to activate it.

      trap deactivate {<trap-ID> [<trap-ID>] ... | all}

   Causes trap(s) with specified ID(s) to be deactivated.


      trap remove {<trap-ID> [<trap-ID>] ... | all}

   Removes trap(s) with specified ID(s) from the trap list.
@endnode

@node cmd_volume "Volume"

      VOLume <volume>

   Sets the volume of the beep to be used. When zero, the screen is
   flashed instead. When positive, the usual VT100 beep is sounded.
   when negative, a higher-pitched shorter beep is used. This is, however,
   superseded by any "BEEPFunction" setting.
@endnode

@node cmd_wait "Wait"

      WAIT <character string> [@{"<timeout>" link cmd_timeouts}]

   Waits until the specified character string is received from the host,
   or, if specified, until the timeout period has expired. If this is the
   last command before returning to a ARexx process, the return code will
   reflect that a timeout occurred. Wait traps with timeout are equivalent
   to "on <character string> continue; delay <timeout>;" except that
   contrary to "on" traps, the "wait" trap is only valid for one occurrence.
   The character string is parsed for @{"ARP style escape" link cmd_ARP} sequences.
@endnode

@node cmd_wedge "Wedge"

      WEDGE <item> <port name>

   Currently only one item can be wedged: KEYStrokes. If the specified
   port name exists, a REXX message will be sent to that port of the form:

      KEYSTROKE <code> <qualifier> <iaddress> <character>

   where the code and qualifier numbers are the key code and lowest
   order 8 qualifier bits of the key pressed by the user. Iaddress keeps a
   history of previous keystrokes, while the character is the translation
   of code and qualifier using the current default keymap. If no translation
   is available, this field will be absent. Note, that the special case
   where the space bar was pressed will look the same.
@endnode

@node cmd_window "Window"

      WINDOW {<leftedge> <topedge> <width> <height> | OPEN | CLOSE}

   Called with any of the first four arguments, allows you to size
   VLT's main window. All arguments are optional. Specifying 0 for width
   and/or height will cause the window to open to the right and/or bottom
   edge of the physical display. Missing arguments default to 0, but the
   arguments must be given in the order specified above, so, for example,
   you cannot omit <leftedge> if you wish to specify <topedge>. VLT will
   check to see if the dimensions given are feasible, but only if the
   main window is already open. If the window size is set while the window
   is closed, subsequent opening of the window may not work if the sizes
   are too large; VLT will try to open the window again, probably with
   the standard 640 by 200 sizes. The size is remembered if you close and
   then reopen the window, or if you switch to a custom screen and then
   back to the Workbench during the same session.

   Called with the "open" option, this command activates VLT's VT100 screen,
   but has no effect if the VT100 screen is already active. Called with the
   close subcommand, this command closes down VLT's screen without clearing
   it. When the window is reopened, the text that used to be there will
   still be there.
@endnode

@node cmd_workbenchcolors "Workbenchcolors"

      WORkbenchcolors @{"<switch>" link cmd_yot}

   When this option is ON, uses the Workbench colors rather than the saved
   custom screen colors. Note that this command does not change the pen
   assignments (see the @{"COLOR" link cmd_color} command).
@endnode

@node cmd_wrap "Wrap"

      WRAP @{"<switch>" link cmd_yot}  

   Switches wrapping of long lines on or off. When set, lines are broken
   at the current maximum column number and the remainder is displayed
   on the next line. When off, lines are not wrapped, and the cursor
   remains at the maximum column accessible while overwriting the last
   character with all following characters according to VT100 standard.
@endnode

@node cmd_xmodemmode "Xmodemmode"

      XMOdemmode {1K | 128 | CHecksum | CRc}

   Sets up to two XMODEM options.
   Options not specified will be carried over from the previous setting.
@endnode

@node cmd_xpr "Xpr"

      XPR INIT <init string>

   Sends the specified initialization string to the current protocol.
   See the documentation of the protocol.

      XPR SELect <xprname>.library

   Selects a different external protocol.
   In older versions of VLT, one used to have to specify the command
   "transfer protocol external" in order to actually select the new protocol.
   This is now implicit. See also the @{"transfer" link cmd_transfer} command.
@endnode
